# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-lebaron
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The **Tucker 48**, originally named and still commonly referred to as the **Tucker Torpedo**, was an automobile conceived by Preston Tucker while in Ypsilanti, Michigan, and briefly produced in Chicago, Illinois, in 1948.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker suspected that the Big Three automakers and Michigan Senator Homer S.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Ferguson had a role in the Tucker Corporation's demise.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The 48's original proposed price was said to be $1,000, but the actual selling price was closer to $4,000.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The 1988 movie *Tucker: The Man and His Dream* is based on the saga surrounding the car's production.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The film's director, Francis Ford Coppola, was a Tucker owner and displayed his vehicle on the grounds of his winery.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The Tucker 48 is often referred to as the Tucker Torpedo.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] However, the Torpedo was actually a prototype, and the name was never used for the production model, which was officially called the "Tucker 48".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] After World War II, the public was ready for new car designs, but the Big Three Detroit automakers had not developed any new models since 1941 because their resources had been diverted towards producing war materiel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This provided opportunities for new, small automakers which could develop new cars faster than the huge legacy automakers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Studebaker was the first to introduce an all-new postwar model series in the ponton style which had just gone mainstream, but Tucker took a different track, designing a safe car with innovative features and modern styling.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] His specifications called for a water-cooled aluminum block flat-6 rear engine, disc brakes, four-wheel independent suspension, fuel injection, the location of all instruments within reach of the steering wheel, seat belts and a padded dashboard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Before the war's end, Preston Tucker began working on plans for his new automobile.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In the summer of 1944, he hired noted car designer George S.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Lawson worked on the project for over a year and a half before his design debuted publicly, beginning about February 1946 and found as late as a year later in March 1947.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Lawson was named the Tucker Corporation's "chief stylist" in February 1946, immediately upon the company's formation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In December 1946, Lawson resigned from the company after a disagreement with Preston Tucker, and shortly thereafter, stylist Alex Tremulis of local Chicago design firm Tammen & Denison was hired and furthered the development of the Lawson design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker gave Tammen & Denison and Tremulis a three-month contract, which expired in March 1947 and was not renewed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The culmination of Tremulis' efforts during this phase of design development was featured in a full-page advertisement run in numerous national newspapers in March 1947.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tremulis' design was based directly upon the work of George Lawson, but incorporated his own artistic flair.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Simultaneous with Tremulis' departure, Preston Tucker hired a team of five designers (Read Viemeister, Budd Steinhilber, Tucker Madawick, Hal Bergstrom and Phillip Egan) from the New York design firm J.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Gordon Lippincott, who updated Tremulis' design just as Tremulis had done with Lawson's.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] After a month's absence, Tremulis was rehired and the two independent design groups developed full-size clay models side by side in direct competition.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Surviving photographs of the two models reveal that Tremulis' clay design remained unchanged from his March 1947 advertisement proposal and was not chosen for production.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The passenger side of the Lippincott team's clay model (they submitted two designs), which incorporated the side profile developed by Tremulis prior to their arrival, was chosen virtually intact for the production automobile's styling.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The SEC, however, failed to prove its case, and Tucker was acquitted of all charges in January 1950.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tremulis, like George Lawson, was eventually named the Tucker Corporation's "chief stylist", although the first reference to him holding this position does not appear until 1948, after the Tucker 48's exterior styling was completed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The Tucker automobile was originally named the "Torpedo", but was changed to "Tucker '48" around the time of Lawson's departure and Tremulis' arrival, reportedly because Tucker did not want to remind the public of the horrors of World War II.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Despite the name change, the Tucker 48 is still often referred to as the Tucker Torpedo.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Alex Tremulis has claimed responsibility for dubbing the first prototype automobile the "Tin Goose", a name which is presently used in an affectionate manner but at the time was considered derogatory.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The Tucker was a pioneer in terms of engineering and safety features.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A rear engine, rear wheel drive configuration had been employed in Tatras and Volkswagens, and headlamps that turned with the front wheels had been available since the 1920s, but they would have been firsts for a modern American production car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The most recognizable feature of the Tucker 48, was a third directional headlamp.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Centrally located, it would activate at steering angles of greater than 10 degrees to light the car's path around corners.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] At the time, 17 states had laws against cars having more than two headlights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker fabricated a cover for the center light for use in these states.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The car had a rear engine and rear-wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A perimeter frame surrounded the vehicle for crash protection, as well as a roll bar integrated into the roof.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The steering box was behind the front axle to protect the driver in a front-end accident.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The instrument panel and all controls were within easy reach of the steering wheel, and the dashboard was padded for safety.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The windshield was made of shatterproof glass and designed to pop out in a collision to protect occupants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The car's parking brake had a separate key so it could be locked in place to prevent theft.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The doors extended into the roof, to ease entry and exit.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Each Tucker that was built differed somewhat from the previous car, as each car built was basically a "prototype" where design features and engineering concepts were tried, improved, or discarded throughout the production cycle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The door releases on the interior of the Tucker came from the Lincoln Zephyr.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The steering columns used in the Tucker were donated by Ford and are from the 1941 Lincoln.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Preston Tucker held a patent for a collapsible steering column design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A glove box was added to the front door panels instead of the more conventional location in the dashboard to provide space for the "crash chamber" that the Tucker is now famous for.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This is a padded area ahead of the passenger seat, free from obstructions, providing the front seat passengers an area to protect themselves in the event of an accident.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The engine and transmission were mounted on a separate subframe which was secured with only six bolts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The entire drive train could thus be lowered and removed from the car in minutes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker envisioned loaner engines being quickly swapped in for service in just 30 minutes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker envisioned several other innovations that were later abandoned.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Magnesium wheels, disc brakes, fuel injection, self-sealing tubeless tires, and a direct-drive torque converter transmission were all evaluated or tested, but were dropped on the final prototype due to cost, engineering complexity, and lack of time to develop.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker initially tried to develop an innovative engine, with help from Ben Parsons, then owner and president of the Fuelcharger Corporation, and would later be Tucker's VP of engineering.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It was a 589 cubic inches (9.7 L) flat-6 cylinder with hemispherical combustion chambers, fuel injection, and overhead valves operated by oil pressure rather than a camshaft.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] An oil pressure distributor was mounted in line with the ignition distributor and delivered appropriately timed direct oil pressure to open each valve at proper intervals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The oil pressure fed to each valve was "timed" by intake and exhaust eccentrics and measured by spring-loaded plungers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It had large pistons built of aluminum and magnesium castings with steel-plated cylinder linings.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This unique engine was designed to idle at 100 rpm and cruise at 250–1200 rpm through the use of direct-drive torque converters on each driving wheel instead of a transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It was designed to produce almost 200 hp (149 kW) and 450 lb⋅ft (610 N⋅m) of torque at only 1800 rpm.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] When cruising at 60 mph (100 km/h), it would only turn at approximately 1000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] These features would have been auto industry firsts in 1948, but as engine development proceeded, problems appeared.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Six prototypes of the 589 engine were built, but it was installed only in the test chassis and the first prototype.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The world premiere of the much-hyped Tucker 48 car was set for June 19, 1947.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Over 3,000 people showed up at the factory in Chicago for lunch, a train tour of the plant, and the unveiling of the first prototype.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The unveiling appeared doomed, however, as last-minute problems cropped up.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The night before the premiere, two of the prototype's independent suspension arms snapped under the car's weight.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] (The prototype was extremely heavy, much heavier than the other 48s.) Minor engine problems were fixed, and the car was presentable by the time of the premiere.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] However, the experimental 589 engine was extremely loud.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker told the band to play as loud as possible to drown out the noise.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Additionally the high-voltage starter required the use of outside power to get the engine started, so Tucker had the engineering team keep the engine running during the entire event, fearing that the public would see how much effort was required to get the engine started.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] As the car was driven on to the platform, the liquid coolant boiled over and some steam escaped from the car, but no one seemed to notice.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Drew Pearson, one of the top newspaper columnists of his time, reported publicly that the car was a fraud because it could not go backward and it went "goose-geese" going down the road.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Although this problem was limited to the first prototype only, a symptom of the speed with which the first car was put together, the damage to the car's reputation was done, and a storm of negative media followed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker suffered another setback when his bids to obtain two steel mills to provide raw materials for his cars were rejected by the War Assets Administration under a shroud of questionable politics.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker had promised 150 hp (112 kW), but his innovative engine was not working out.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The valve train proved problematic and the engine only produced approximately 88 hp (66 kW).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The high oil pressure required a 24-volt electrical system, up to 60 volts to get it started, and a long cranking time at start-up.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Additionally, the oil pressure required to maintain valve function was not achieved until the engine was turning at higher engine speeds and Tucker's engineers struggled with keeping the valve train working at idle and lower engine speeds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Having wasted nearly a year trying to make the 589 work, Tucker started looking for alternatives.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The company first tried the Lycoming aircraft engine, but it would not fit in the car's rear engine compartment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] An air-cooled flat-6 engine, the Franklin O-335 made by Air Cooled Motors (and originally intended for the Bell 47 helicopter), fit, and its 166 hp (124 kW) pleased Tucker.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] He purchased four samples for $5,000 each, and his engineers converted the 334 cubic inches (5,470 cc) engine to water cooling (a decision that has puzzled historians ever since).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The Franklin engine was heavily modified by Tucker's engineers, including Eddie Offutt and Tucker's son Preston, Jr. at his Ypsilanti machine shop.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Using an aircraft engine in an automotive application required significant modification; thus, very few parts of the original Franklin engine were retained in the final Tucker engine.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This durable modification of the engine was tested at maximum power for 150 hours, the equivalent of 18,000 miles (29,000 km), at full throttle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker quickly bought Air Cooled Motors for $1.8 million to secure the engine source, then canceled all of the company's aircraft contracts so its resources could be focused on making automotive engines.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This was a significant decision, since at the time of Tucker's purchase, Air Cooled Motors held over 65% of post-war U.S. aviation engine production contracts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] With the horizontal, between-the-wheels 589 engine and its double torque converter(s) (and no reverse) drive system out, Tucker now needed a transmission to mate with the Franklin O-335.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This engine was also horizontal, but its driveshaft pointed towards the front of the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It was discovered, after a few sketches were made, that it was theoretically possible to adapt a previous transmission design intended for front-engine/front wheel drive use.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This transmission served as a temporary "fix" for a very real problem for the success of the Tucker.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This transmission was originally designed to sit behind a standard V8 engine, pointing towards the driven front wheels of the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] However, this transmission had a poor reputation following its original use in the Cord 810: In 1936, when the Cord 810 made its debut at the New York Automobile show, the transmissions were so problematic that they were mostly shown without any transmission installed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Problems abounded until the last Cord was produced in 1937.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The Cord transmissions, even with refurbishing, were initially inadequate for the power and torque of the O-335 engine.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] They lacked adequate lubrication and the main shaft was so long that it warped under load (causing gears to pop out of play), and the gear-teeth were quite weak.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Nevertheless, this transmission worked well enough for the Tucker: it provided an adequate (albeit fragile) transmission, with a reverse gear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The company sent several of its staff, including Preston Tucker Jr., on a campaign to buy used Cord transmissions for reconditioning; a total of 22 used transmissions were acquired from junkyards and used car dealers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] These transmissions were taken to the Ypsilanti Machine And Tool Company to be refurbished, mated to the O-335 engine and found to work.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It was consequently decided that the 12-year old Cord design would become the standard manual transmission for the 1948 and subsequent Tucker automobiles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Since the Y-1 transmission was not yet available, 18 of the 22 Cord transmissions were deemed usable and were installed in production Tucker vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Several of the cars have survived with Cord transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Ypsilanti Machine and Tool Company, which was tapped to recondition the Cord units, began immediately redesigning the transmission for mass production for Tucker.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This new design, which had few similar parts to the Cord transmission, still used the same basic indirect transmission design, but had all new gearing, shafts and electro-vacuum controls.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker and his engineers modified it, installing stronger gears and lengthening the case.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The modified Cord transmission was named the Tucker Y-1 (Ypsilanti-1) and was installed in a few Tuckers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Both also used a Bendix designed electric vacuum shift mechanism with no mechanical linkage to the steering column shift lever.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] These EVS's had problems of their own with electrical connections and vacuum leaks that hindered shifting, so a new fully mechanical shift design would have been needed, had the Tucker made it into 1949.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] To solve the transmission problems with a new final transmission design, Warren Rice, creator of the Buick Dynaflow transmission, was consulted.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A unique continuously variable transmission called the "Tuckermatic" was designed, which was strong enough to handle the Franklin O-335's power and torque.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It was a simple but effective design with a single, rear-mounted torque converter and only 27 basic moving parts which was about 90 fewer than normally required for a contemporary automatic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The variable pitch torque converter allowed a continuously variable drive ratio with two forward gears and one reverse gear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The only surviving car with a Tuckermatic installed had a standard column shift lever, with a three position quadrant on the steering column.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Up was reverse, the middle was neutral, and down was drive.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Due to the Tuckermatic's design, no lower gear selections were necessary, hence there was no need for a multi gated selector like other automatics.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Three versions of the Tuckermatic were made: the R-1, R-1-2, and R-3 (R for Warren Rice, its designer).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The first version, the R-1, was not installed on any of the final cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It required the engine to be off in order to select a gear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The R-1-2 was improved by adding a layshaft brake to allow gear selection while the engine was running.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This version was installed on cars #1026 and 1042 only.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The R-3 version had further improvements including a centrifugal clutch to help shifting between forward and reverse even further, and may have been destined for car #1048 for further testing.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This had the added advantage of improving weight distribution in the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A Borg-Warner based, 3-speed automatic was supposedly tested and was installed on car #1048 at some point when the company was in business, although no histories written ever mentioned such a drive.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] That said, Tucker ultimately wanted to design his own transmission for the final car, which came to fruition with the Tuckermatic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In 1949, #1048 was sold at the receivership auction without a transmission installed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Today, #1048 has the 4 speed pre-selector transmission that was used on all but two of the original 50 pilot models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It is likely this transmission was privately installed after the auction, and that the unit was the Ypsilanti-built Y-1 transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Suspension designs, especially the front suspension, had to be changed throughout development.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Rather than steel springs, Tucker used an elastomeric (rubber) 4-wheel independent suspension similar to what was used on the race cars he developed with Harry Miller at the Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The rubber elastomers were developed with assistance from the Firestone Tire Company and used a special vulcanization process to produce a specific spring rate.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker's suspension designs were plagued with severe stiffness throughout development, which, while good for handling, caused front-wheel corner lift when cornering on uneven surfaces.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The test bed and the prototype had a double-rubber disc type front and rear suspension, similar to Miller's race cars, which was too weak for the weight of a passenger car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] On cars #1001 and 1002 the rear wheels could not be removed without removing the fender or suspension due to the stiffness of the suspension and the rear wheel arch fender design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] From car #1003 on, the rear fender shape was changed so the tire could be removed easily.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Aside from the fender changes, the rear suspension remained the same from car #1001 on.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Three versions of the front suspension were installed in the cars (aside from the rubber-disc style used on the prototype).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Cars #1001–1002 used a rubber torsion tube design, which suffered from severe toe-in during heavy braking.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker then switched to a rubber sandwich type suspension (with a rubber block sandwiched between the upper and lower A-arms) on cars #1003–1025, however, this type was severely stiff.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Starting on car #1026, Tucker finally settled on a suspension design with a modified version of the rubber torsion tube with the toe-in braking problem corrected.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Having raised $17,000,000 in a stock issue, one of the first speculative IPOs, Tucker needed more money to continue development of the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] He sold dealerships and distributorships throughout the country.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Another money maker was the Tucker Accessories Program.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In order to secure a spot on the Tucker waiting list, future buyers could purchase accessories, like seat covers, radio, and luggage, before their car was built.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This brought in an additional $2,000,000.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] With the final design in place, Preston Tucker took the pre-production cars on the road to show them in towns across the country.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The cars were an instant success, with crowds gathering wherever they stopped.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] One report says Tucker was pulled over by a police officer intent on getting a better look at the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] To prove the road-worthiness of his cars, Tucker and his engineers ran several cars at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in several endurance tests.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] During this testing, car #1027 was rolled three times at 95 miles per hour (153 km/h), and the driver (chief mechanic Eddie Offutt) walked away with just bruises.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] During the crash, the windshield popped out as designed, verifying Tucker's safety features were effective.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Afterwards, upon replacing a damaged tire, the car started up and was driven off the track.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] One of Tucker's most innovative business ideas caused trouble for the company.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] His Accessories Program raised funds by selling accessories before the car was even in production.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] After the war, demand for new cars was greater than dealers could supply and most dealers had waiting lists for new cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Preference was given to returning veterans which meant that non-veterans were bumped down on the waiting lists indefinitely.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker's program allowed potential buyers who purchased Tucker accessories to obtain a guaranteed spot on the Tucker dealer waiting list for a Tucker 48 car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This concept was investigated by the U.S.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Securities and Exchange Commission and the United States Attorney, and led to an indictment of company executives.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Although all charges were eventually dropped, the negative publicity destroyed the company and halted production of the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The first Tucker produced was a prototype sedan, known as the "Tin Goose".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] 58 frames and bodies were built at the factory.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] From these parts, 36 sedans were finished before the factory was closed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] After the factory closed, but before liquidation of his assets, Tucker retained a core of employees who assembled an additional 14 sedans, for a total of 50.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] A few of the remaining frames and bodies were built into complete cars specifically #1052 and #1057 (the 1949 prototype with design changes), but the fate of the others is unknown.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Lauderdale, Florida, fairgrounds owner Nick Jenin purchased over ten Tuckers, the original Tucker testbed chassis, numerous Tucker parts, photos and documents.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] He developed a traveling display called "The Fabulous Tuckers".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] He hauled the cars and memorabilia around the country for nearly 10 years displaying them at fairgrounds and car shows.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] His display highlighted the questionable policies and SEC fraud investigation which brought Tucker down.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] When the cars appear at auction, which is rare, they command prices attained by only a few marquee cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In August 2010, Tucker #1045 sold for $1.127 million, while Tucker #1043 went for $2.915 million at an auction in 2012.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] In 1997, Rob Ida Automotive started work on a replica of the Tucker 48, which culminated in the release and marketing of the 2001 Ida Automotive New Tucker 48.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] This replica faithfully recreates the Tucker's external bodywork, but is built on a hotrod chassis with resin-infused plastic body panels.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] The paint and wheels reflect modern hotrod styling, and the interior is fully modernized.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] It is powered by a mid-mounted Cadillac Northstar V8.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Its claimed performance is 0–60 in 7 seconds, with a top speed in excess of 120 mph (190 km/h).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/1948-tucker-sedan] Tucker #1004 was briefly raced in the NASCAR Grand National series in the early 1950s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An **airbag** or **supplemental inflatable restraint** is a vehicle occupant-restraint system using a bag designed to inflate in milliseconds during a collision and then deflate afterwards.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] It consists of an airbag cushion, a flexible fabric bag, an inflation module, and an impact sensor.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The purpose of the airbag is to provide a vehicle occupant with soft cushioning and restraint during a collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] It can reduce injuries between the flailing occupant and the vehicle's interior.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag provides an energy-absorbing surface between the vehicle's occupants and a steering wheel, instrument panel, body pillar, headliner, and windshield.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Modern vehicles may contain up to ten airbag modules in various configurations, including driver, passenger, side-curtain, seat-mounted, door-mounted, B- and C-pillar mounted side-impact, knee bolster, inflatable seat belt, and pedestrian airbag modules.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] During a crash, the vehicle's crash sensors provide crucial information to the airbag electronic controller unit (ECU), including collision type, angle, and severity of impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Using this information, the airbag ECU's crash algorithm determines if the crash event meets the criteria for deployment and triggers various firing circuits to deploy one or more airbag modules within the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbag module deployments are activated through a pyrotechnic process designed to be used once as a supplemental restraint system for the vehicle's seat belt systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Newer side-impact airbag modules consist of compressed-air cylinders that are triggered in the event of a side-on vehicle impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The first commercial designs were introduced in passenger automobiles during the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These designs saw limited success and caused some fatalities.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Broad commercial adoption of airbags occurred in many markets during the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbags are considered "passive" restraints and act as a supplement to "active" restraints.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Because no action by a vehicle occupant is required to activate or use the airbag, it is considered a "passive" device.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This is in contrast to seat belts, which are considered "active" devices because the vehicle occupant must act to enable them.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This terminology is not related to active and passive safety, which are, respectively, systems designed to prevent collisions in the first place, and systems designed to minimize the effects of collisions once they occur.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In this use, a car Anti-lock braking system qualifies as an active-safety device, while both its seat belts and airbags qualify as passive-safety devices.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Terminological confusion can arise from the fact that passive devices and systems—those requiring no input or action by the vehicle occupant—can operate independently in an active manner; an airbag is one such device.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Vehicle safety professionals are generally careful in their use of language to avoid this sort of confusion.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, advertising principles sometimes prevent such semantic caution in the consumer marketing of safety features.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Further confusing the terminology, the aviation safety community uses the terms "active" and "passive" in the *opposite* sense from the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag "for the covering of aeroplane and other vehicle parts" traces its origins to a United States patent, submitted in 1919 by two dentists from Birmingham, Arthur Parrott and Harold Round.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Air-filled bladders were in use as early as 1951.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag specifically for automobile use is credited independently to the American John W.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Hetrick, who filed for an airbag patent on 5 August 1952, that was granted #2,649,311 by the United States Patent Office on 18 August 1953.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] German patent #896,312 filed for by engineer Walter Linderer on 6 October 1951 was issued on 12 November 1953, approximately three months after American John Hetrick.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbags proposed by Hetrick and Linderer were based on compressed air released by a spring, bumper contact, or by the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Later research during the 1960s showed that compressed air could not inflate the mechanical airbags fast enough to ensure maximum safety, leading to the current chemical and electrical airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In patent applications, manufacturers sometimes use the term "inflatable occupant restraint systems".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Hetrick was an industrial engineer and member of the United States Navy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] His airbag design, however, only came about when he combined his experiences working with navy torpedoes with his desire to protect his family on the road.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Despite working with the major automobile manufacturers of his time, Hetrick was unable to attract investment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Although airbags are now required in every automobile sold in the United States, Hetrick's 1951 patent filing serves as an example of a "valuable" invention with little economic value to its inventor.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Its first commercial use was not implemented until after the patent expired in 1971, at which point the airbag was installed in a few experimental Ford cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1964, a Japanese automobile engineer, Yasuzaburou Kobori (小堀保三郎), started developing an airbag "safety net" system.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] His design harnessed an explosive to inflate an airbag, for which he was later awarded patents in 14 countries.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] He died in 1975, before seeing the widespread adoption of airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1967, a breakthrough in developing airbag crash sensors came when Allen K.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Breed invented a ball-in-tube mechanism for crash detection.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Under his system, an electromechanical sensor with a steel ball attached to a tube by a magnet would inflate an airbag in under 30 milliseconds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A small explosion of sodium azide was used instead of compressed air during inflation for the first time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Breed Corporation then marketed this innovation to Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A similar "Auto-Ceptor" crash-restraint, developed by the Eaton, Yale & Towne company for Ford, was soon also offered as an automatic safety system in the United States, while the Italian Eaton-Livia company offered a variant with localized air cushions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In the early 1970s, General Motors began offering cars equipped with airbags, initially in government fleet-purchased 1973 Chevrolet Impala sedans.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These cars came with a 1974-style Oldsmobile instrument panel and a unique steering wheel that contained the driver-side airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Two of these cars were crash tested after 20 years and the airbags deployed perfectly.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An early example of the airbag cars survives as of 2009.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] GM's Oldsmobile Toronado was the first domestic U.S. vehicle to include a passenger airbag in 1973.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] General Motors marketed its first airbag modules under the "Air Cushion Restraint System" name, or ACRS.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The automaker discontinued the option for its 1977 model year, citing a lack of consumer interest.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Ford and GM then spent years lobbying against air-bag requirements, claiming that the devices were unfeasible and inappropriate.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Chrysler made driver-side airbags standard on 1988 and 1989 models, but airbags did not become widespread in American cars until the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbags for passenger cars were introduced in the United States in the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When seat-belt usage rates in the country were quite low compared to modern-day, Ford built experimental cars with airbags in 1971.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Allstate operated a fleet of 200 Mercury Montereys and showed the reliability of airbags as well as their operation in crash testing, which also was promoted by the insurance company in popular magazine advertisements.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] General Motors followed in 1973 using full-sized Chevrolet vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The early fleet of experimental GM vehicles equipped with airbags experienced seven fatalities, one of which was later suspected to have been caused by the airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1974, GM made its ACRS system (which consisted of a padded lower dashboard and a passenger-side air bag) available as a regular production option (RPO code AR3) in full-sized Cadillac, Buick and Oldsmobile models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The GM cars from the 1970s equipped with ACRS had a driver-side airbag, and a driver-side knee restraint.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The passenger-side airbag protected both front passengers, and unlike most modern systems, integrated a knee and torso cushion while also having a dual-stage deployment dictated by force of the impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The cars equipped with ACRS had lap belts for all seating positions, but lacked shoulder belts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Shoulder belts were already mandatory in the United States on closed cars without airbags for the driver and outer front passenger, but GM chose to market its airbags as a substitute for shoulder belts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The early development of airbags coincided with international interest in automobile safety legislation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some safety experts advocated a performance-based occupant-protection standard rather than one mandating a particular technical solution (which could rapidly become outdated and prove to not be a cost-effective approach).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Less emphasis was placed on other designs as countries successfully mandated seat belt restrictions, however.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The auto industry and research and regulatory communities have moved away from their initial view of the airbag as a seat-belt replacement, and the bags are now nominally designated as **supplemental restraint systems** (**SRS**) or supplemental inflatable restraints.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1981, Mercedes-Benz introduced the airbag in West Germany as an option on its flagship saloon model, S-Class (W126).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In the Mercedes system, the sensors automatically tensioned the seat belts to reduce occupants' motion on impact and then deployed the airbag on impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This integrated the seat belts and the airbag into a restraint system, rather than the airbag being considered an alternative to the seat belt.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1987, the Porsche 944 Turbo became the first car to have driver and passenger airbags as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Porsche 944 and 944S had this as an available option.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The same year also had the first airbag in a Japanese car, the Honda Legend.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1988, Chrysler became the first United States automaker to fit a driver-side airbag as standard equipment, which was offered in six different models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The following year, Chrysler became the first US auto manufacturer to offer driver-side airbags in all its new passenger models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Chrysler also began featuring the airbags in advertisements showing how the devices had saved lives that helped the public know the value of them and safety became a selling advantage in the late 1980s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] All versions of the Chrysler minivans came with airbags starting for the 1991 model year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1993, The Lincoln Motor Company boasted that all vehicles in their model line were equipped with dual airbags, one for the driver's side and another for the passenger's side.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The 1993 Jeep Grand Cherokee became the first SUV to offer a driver-side airbag when it was launched in 1992.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Driver and passenger airbags became standard equipment in all Dodge Intrepid, Eagle Vision, and Chrysler Concorde sedans ahead of any safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Early 1993 saw the 4-millionth airbag-equipped Chrysler vehicle roll off the assembly line.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In October 1993, the Dodge Ram became the first pickup truck with a standard driver-side airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The first known collision between two airbag-equipped automobiles took place on 12 March 1990 in Virginia, USA.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A 1989 Chrysler LeBaron crossed the center line and hit another 1989 Chrysler LeBaron in a head-on collision, causing both driver airbags to deploy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The drivers suffered only minor injuries despite extensive damage to the vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The United States Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act of 1991 required passenger cars and light trucks built after 1 September 1998 to have airbags for the driver and the front passenger.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In the United States, NHTSA estimated that airbags had saved over 4,600 lives by 1 September 1999; however, the crash deployment experience of the early 1990s installations indicated that some fatalities and serious injuries were in fact caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1998, NHTSA initiated new rules for advanced airbags that gave automakers more flexibility in devising effective technological solutions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The revised rules also required improved protection for occupants of different sizes regardless of whether they use seat belts, while minimizing the risk to infants, children, and other occupants caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In Europe, airbags were almost unheard of until the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Citroën, Fiat, Nissan, Hyundai, Peugeot, Renault, and Volkswagen followed shortly afterwards.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] By 1999, finding a new mass-market car without an airbag at least as optional equipment was difficult, and some late 1990s products, such as the Volkswagen Golf Mk4, also featured side airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Peugeot 306 is one example of the European automotive mass-market evolution: starting in early 1993, most of these models did not even offer a driver's airbag as an option, but by 1999, even side airbags were available on several variants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Audi was late to offer airbag systems on a broader scale, since even in the 1994 model year, its popular models did not offer airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Instead, the German automaker until then relied solely on its proprietary cable-based procon-ten restraint system.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Variable force-deployment front airbags were developed to help minimize injury from the airbag itself.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Many new cars in Latin America, including the Kia Rio, Kia Picanto, Hyundai Grand i10, Mazda 2, Chevrolet Spark and the Chevrolet Onix, are often sold without airbags, as neither airbags nor automatic braking systems in new cars are compulsory in many Latin American countries.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some require the installation of a minimum of only two airbags in new cars which many in this market have.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Citroën C4 provided the first "shaped" driver airbag, made possible by this car's unusual fixed-hub steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 2019, Honda announced it would introduce a new front passenger airbag technology.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Developed by Autoliv and Honda R&D in Ohio, United States, this new airbag design features three inflatable chambers connected across the front by a "noninflatable sail panel." The two outer chambers are larger than the middle chamber.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When the airbag deploys, the sail panel cushions the occupant's head from the impact of hitting the airbag, and the three chambers hold the occupant's head in place, like a catcher's mitt.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The goal of the tri-chamber airbag is to help "arrest high-speed movement" of the head, thereby reducing the likelihood of concussion injuries in a collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The first vehicle to come with the tri-chamber airbag installed from the factory was in 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Acura TLX.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Honda hopes that the new technology will soon make its way to all vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Mercedes began offering rear passengers protection in frontal collisions in September 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W223).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The W223 S-Class is the first car equipped with rear seat airbags that use gas to inflate supporting structures that unfold and extend a bag that fills with ambient air, instead of conventional fully gas-inflated airbags that are widely used in automotive airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Essentially, two types of side airbags are commonly used today - the side-torso airbag and the side-curtain airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] More recently, center airbags are becoming more common in the European market.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Most vehicles equipped with side-curtain airbags also include side-torso airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, some, such as the Chevrolet Cobalt, 2007–09 model Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra, and 2009–12 Dodge Ram do not feature the side-torso airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] From around 2000, side-impact airbags became commonplace on even low- to mid-range vehicles, such as the smaller-engined versions of the Ford Fiesta and Peugeot 206, and curtain airbags were also becoming regular features on mass-market cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Toyota Avensis, launched in 2003, was the first mass-market car to be sold in Europe with nine airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Side-impact airbags or side-torso airbags are a category of airbags usually located in the seat or door panel, and inflate between the seat occupant and the door.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These airbags are designed to reduce the risk of injury to the pelvic and lower abdomen regions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Most vehicles are now being equipped with different types of designs, to help reduce injury and ejection from the vehicle in rollover crashes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] More recent side-airbag designs include a two-chamber system; a firmer lower chamber for the pelvic region and softer upper chamber for the ribcage.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Swedish company Autoliv AB was granted a patent on side-impact airbags, and they were first offered as an option in 1994 on the 1995 Volvo 850, and as standard equipment on all Volvo cars made after 1995.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1997, Saab introduced the first combined head and torso airbags with the launch of the Saab 9-5.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some cars, such as the 2010 Volkswagen Polo Mk.5 have combined head- and torso-side airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These are fitted in the backrest of the front seats and protect the head and the torso.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1997, the BMW 7 Series and 5 Series were fitted with tubular-shaped head side airbags (inflatable tubular structure), the "Head Protection System (HPS)" as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This airbag was designed to offer head protection in side impact collisions and also maintained inflation for up to seven seconds for rollover protection.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, this tubular-shaped airbag design has been quickly replaced by an inflatable 'curtain' airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In May 1998, Toyota began offering a side-curtain airbag deploying from the roof on the Progrés.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1998, the Volvo S80 was given roof-mounted curtain airbags to protect both front and rear passengers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags were then made standard equipment on all new Volvo cars from 2000 except for the first-generation C70, which received an enlarged side-torso airbag that also protects the head of front-seat occupants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The second-generation C70 convertible received the world's first door-mounted, side-curtain airbags that deployed upwards.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags have been said to reduce brain injury or fatalities by up to 45% in a side impact with an SUV.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These airbags come in various forms (e.g., tubular, curtain, door-mounted) depending on the needs of the application.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Many recent SUVs and MPVs have a long inflatable curtain airbag that protects all rows of seats.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In many vehicles, the curtain airbags are programmed to deploy during some/all frontal impacts to manage passenger kinetics (e.g. head hitting B-pillar on the rebound), especially in offset crashes such as the IIHS's small overlap crash test.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Roll-sensing curtain airbags are designed to stay inflated for a longer duration of time, cover a larger proportion of the window, and be deployed in a roll-over crash.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] They offer protection to occupants' heads and help to prevent ejection.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] SUVs and pickups are more likely to be equipped with RSCAs due to their higher probability of rolling over and often a switch can disable the feature in case the driver wants to take the vehicle off-road.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 2009, Toyota developed the first production rear-seat center airbag designed to reduce the severity of secondary injuries to rear passengers in a side collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This system deploys from the rear center seat first appearing in on the Crown Majesta.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In late 2012, General Motors with supplier Takata introduced a front center airbag; it deploys from the driver's seat.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Hyundai Motor Group announced its development of a center-side airbag on September 18, 2019, installed inside the driver's seat.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some Volkswagen vehicles in 2022 equipped with center airbags include the ID.3 and the Golf.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Polestar 2 also includes a center airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Škoda makes center airbags standard equipment in cars and Honda wants to add center airbags to their advanced airbag system in 2023.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] With EuroNCAP updating its testing guidelines in 2020, European and Australian market vehicles increasingly use front-center airbags, rear torso airbags, and rear seat belt pre-tensioners.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The second driver-side and separate knee airbag was used in the Kia Sportage SUV and has been standard equipment since then.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag is located beneath the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Toyota Caldina introduced the first driver-side SRS knee airbag on the Japanese market in 2002.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Toyota Avensis became the first vehicle sold in Europe equipped with a driver's knee airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The EuroNCAP reported on the 2003 Avensis, "There has been much effort to protect the driver's knees and legs and a knee airbag worked well." Since then certain models have also included front-passenger knee airbags, which deploy near or over the glove compartment in a crash.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Knee airbags are designed to reduce leg injury.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The knee airbag has become increasingly common since 2000.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 2008, the new Toyota iQ microcar featured the first production rear-curtain shield airbag to protect the rear occupants' heads in the event of a rear-end impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Another feature of the Toyota iQ was a seat-cushion airbag in the passenger seat to prevent the pelvis from diving below the lap belt during a frontal impact or submarining.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Later Toyota models such as the Yaris added the feature to the driver's seat, as well.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The seat-belt airbag is designed to better distribute the forces experienced by a buckled person in a crash using an increased seat belt area.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This is done to reduce possible injuries to the rib cage or chest of the belt wearer.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Cessna Aircraft also introduced seat belt airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbag(s) mounted to the exterior of vehicles, so-called "pedestrian airbags", are designed to reduce injuries in the event of a vehicle to a pedestrian collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When a collision is detected the airbag will deploy and cover hard areas, such as a-pillars and bonnet edges, before they can be struck by the pedestrian.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When introduced in 2012 the Volvo V40 included the world's first pedestrian airbag as standard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] As a result, the V40 ranked highest (88%) in the EuroNCAP's pedestrian tests.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Suppliers of SRS airbags include Autoliv, Daicel, TRW, and JSS (which owns Breed, Key Safety Systems, and Takata).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The majority of impact sensors of airbags are manufactured by the Lanka Harness Company in Sri Lanka.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbags in the vehicle are controlled by a central airbag control unit (ACU), a specific type of ECU.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The ACU monitors several related sensors within the vehicle, including accelerometers, impact sensors, side (door) pressure sensors, wheel speed sensors, gyroscopes, brake pressure sensors, and seat occupancy sensors.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Oftentimes, ACUs log this—and other—sensor data in a circular buffer and record it to onboard non-volatile memory, to provide a snapshot of the crash event for investigators.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] As such, an ACU frequently functions as the vehicle's event data recorder (EDR); not all EDRs are ACUs, and not all ACUs include EDR features.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An ACU typically includes capacitors within its circuitry, so that the module remains powered and able to deploy the airbags if the vehicle's battery connection to the ACU is severed during a crash.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The bag itself and its inflation mechanism are concealed within the steering wheel boss (for the driver), or the dashboard (for the front passenger), behind plastic flaps or doors that are designed to tear open under the force of the bag inflating.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Once the requisite threshold has been reached or exceeded, the airbag control unit will trigger the ignition of a gas generator propellant to rapidly inflate a fabric bag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] As the vehicle occupant collides with and squeezes the bag, the gas escapes in a controlled manner through small vent holes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag's volume and the size of the vents in the bag are tailored to each vehicle type, to spread out the deceleration of (and thus force experienced by) the occupant over time and over the occupant's body, compared to a seat belt alone.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The signals from the various sensors are fed into the airbag control unit, which determines from them the angle of impact, the severity, or the force of the crash, along with other variables.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Depending on the result of these calculations, the ACU may also deploy various additional restraint devices, such as seat belt pre-tensioners, and/or airbags (including frontal bags for driver and front passenger, along with seat-mounted side bags, and "curtain" airbags which cover the side glass).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Each restraint device is typically activated with one or more pyrotechnic devices, commonly called an initiator or electric match.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The electric match, which consists of an electrical conductor wrapped in a combustible material, activates with a current pulse between 1 and 3 amps in less than 2 milliseconds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When the conductor becomes hot enough, it ignites the combustible material, which initiates the gas generator.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In a seat belt pre-tensioner, this hot gas is used to drive a piston that pulls the slack out of the seat belt.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In an airbag, the initiator is used to ignite solid propellant inside the airbag inflator.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The burning propellant generates inert gas which rapidly inflates the airbag in approximately 20 to 30 ms.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An airbag must inflate quickly to be fully inflated by the time the forward-traveling occupant reaches its outer surface.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Typically, the decision to deploy an airbag in a frontal crash is made within 15 to 30 ms after the onset of the crash, and both the driver and passenger airbags are fully inflated within approximately 60 to 80 ms after the first moment of vehicle contact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] If an airbag deploys too late or too slowly, the risk of occupant injury from contact with the inflating airbag may increase.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since more distance typically exists between the passenger and the instrument panel, the passenger airbag is larger and requires more gas to fill it.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Older airbag systems contained a mixture of sodium azide (NaN3), KNO3, and SiO2.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A typical driver-side airbag contains approximately 50–80 grams (1.8–2.8 oz) of NaN3, with the larger passenger-side airbag containing about 250 grams (8.8 oz).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Within about 40 milliseconds of impact, all these components react in three separate reactions that produce nitrogen gas.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The reactions, in order, are as follows.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The first two reactions create 4 molar equivalents of nitrogen gas, and the third converts the remaining reactants to relatively inert potassium silicate and sodium silicate.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] There are ongoing efforts to find alternative compounds so that airbags have less toxic reactants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The reaction of the Sr complex nitrate, (SrOC(N2H3)2·(NO3)2) of carbohydrazide (SrCDH) with various oxidizing agents results in the evolution of N2 and CO2 gases.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The N2 and CO2 gases evolved made up 99% of all gases evolved.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Nearly all of the starting materials will not decompose until reaching temperatures of 500 °C (932 °F) or higher, so this could be a viable option as an airbag gas generator.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since airbags deploy only once and deflate quickly after the initial impact, they will not be beneficial during a subsequent collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In vehicles equipped with a rollover sensing system, accelerometers, and gyroscopes are used to sense the onset of a rollover event.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] If a rollover event is determined to be imminent, side-curtain airbags are deployed to help protect the occupant from contact with the side of the vehicle interior, and also to help prevent occupant ejection as the vehicle rolls over.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] International regulations are performance-based, rather than technology-based, so airbag deployment threshold is a function of overall vehicle design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Unlike crash tests into barriers, real-world crashes typically occur at angles other than directly into the front of the vehicle, and the crash forces usually are not evenly distributed across the front of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Consequently, the relative speed between a striking and struck vehicle required to deploy the airbag in a real-world crash can be much higher than an equivalent barrier crash.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Because airbag sensors measure deceleration, the vehicle speed is not a good indicator of whether an airbag should be deployed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbags can deploy due to the vehicle's undercarriage striking a low object protruding above the roadway due to the resulting deceleration.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The airbag sensor is a MEMS accelerometer, which is a small integrated circuit with integrated micromechanical elements.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The microscopic mechanical element moves in response to rapid deceleration, and this motion causes a change in capacitance, which is detected by the electronics on the chip that then sends a signal to fire the airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The most common MEMS accelerometer in use is the ADXL-50 by Analog Devices, but there are other MEMS manufacturers as well.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Initial attempts using mercury switches did not work well.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Before MEMS, the primary system used to deploy airbags was called a "rolamite".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A rolamite is a mechanical device, consisting of a roller suspended within a tensioned band.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] As a result of the particular geometry and material properties used, the roller is free to translate with little friction or hysteresis.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This device was developed at Sandia National Laboratories.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Rolamite and similar macro-mechanical devices were used in airbags until the mid-1990s after which they were universally replaced with MEMS.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Nearly all airbags are designed to automatically deploy in the event of a vehicle fire when temperatures reach 150–200 °C (302–392 °F).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This safety feature, often termed auto-ignition, helps to ensure that such temperatures do not cause an explosion of the entire airbag module.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Today, airbag triggering algorithms are much more complex, being able to adapt the deployment speed to the crash conditions, and prevent unnecessary deployments.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The algorithms are considered valuable intellectual property.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Experimental algorithms may take into account such factors as the weight of the occupant, the seat location, and seat belt use, as well as even attempt to determine if a baby seat is present.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] When the frontal airbags are to deploy, a signal is sent to the gas generator/inflator unit within the airbag control unit.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An igniter starts a rapid chemical reaction generating primarily nitrogen gas (N2) to fill the airbag making it deploy through the module cover.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some airbag technologies use compressed nitrogen or argon gas with a pyrotechnic operated valve ("hybrid gas generator"), while other technologies use various energetic propellants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Although propellants containing the highly toxic sodium azide (NaN3) were common in early inflator designs, little to no toxic sodium azide has been found on used airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The azide-containing pyrotechnic gas generators contain a substantial amount of the propellant.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The driver-side airbag would contain a canister containing about 50 grams (1.8 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The passenger side container holds about 200 grams (7.1 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] From the onset of the crash, the entire deployment and inflation process is about 0.04 seconds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Because vehicles change speed so quickly in a crash, airbags must inflate rapidly to reduce the risk of the occupant hitting the vehicle's interior.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Advanced airbag technologies are being developed to tailor airbag deployment to the severity of the crash, the size, and posture of the vehicle occupant, belt usage, and how close that person is to the actual airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Many of these systems use multi-stage inflators that deploy less forcefully in stages in moderate crashes than in very severe crashes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Occupant sensing devices let the airbag control unit know if someone is occupying a seat adjacent to an airbag, the mass/weight of the person, whether a seat belt or child restraint is being used, and whether the person is forward in the seat and close to the airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Based on this information and crash severity information, the airbag is deployed at either a high force level, a less forceful level, or not at all.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Adaptive airbag systems may utilize multi-stage airbags to adjust the pressure within the airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The greater the pressure within the airbag, the more force the airbag will exert on the occupants as they come in contact with it.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] These adjustments allow the system to deploy the airbag with a moderate force for most collisions; reserving the maximum force airbag only for the severest of collisions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Additional sensors to determine the location, weight or relative size of the occupants may also be used.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Information regarding the occupants and the severity of the crash are used by the airbag control unit, to determine whether airbags should be suppressed or deployed, and if so, at various output levels.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] A chemical reaction produces a burst of nitrogen to inflate the bag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Once an airbag deploys, deflation begins immediately as the gas escapes through vent(s) in the fabric (or, as it is sometimes called, the cushion) and cools.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Deployment is frequently accompanied by the release of dust-like particles, and gases in the vehicle's interior (called effluent).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Most of this dust consists of cornstarch, french chalk, or talcum powder, which are used to lubricate the airbag during deployment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Newer designs produce effluent primarily consisting of harmless talcum powder/cornstarch and nitrogen gas.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In older designs using an azide-based propellant (usually NaN3), varying amounts of sodium hydroxide nearly always are initially present.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In small amounts this chemical can cause minor irritation to the eyes and/or open wounds; however, with exposure to air, it quickly turns into sodium bicarbonate (baking soda).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, this transformation is not 100% complete, and invariably leaves residual amounts of hydroxide ions from NaOH.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Depending on the type of airbag system, potassium chloride may also be present.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] For most people, the only effect the dust may produce is some minor irritation of the throat and eyes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Generally, minor irritations only occur when the occupant remains in the vehicle for many minutes with the windows closed and no ventilation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, some people with asthma may develop a potentially lethal asthmatic attack from inhaling the dust.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Because of the airbag exit flap design of the steering wheel boss and dashboard panel, these items are not designed to be recoverable if an airbag deploys, meaning that they have to be replaced if the vehicle has not been written off in a collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Moreover, the dust-like particles and gases can cause irreparable cosmetic damage to the dashboard and upholstery, meaning that minor collisions that result in the deployment of airbags can be costly, even if there are no injuries and there is only minor damage to the vehicle structure.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] On 11 July 1984, the United States government amended Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 208 (FMVSS 208) to require cars produced after 1 April 1989 to be equipped with a passive restraint for the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An airbag or an automatic seat belt would meet the requirements of the standard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbag introduction was stimulated by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] However, airbags were not mandatory on light trucks until 1997.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 1998, FMVSS 208 was amended to require dual front airbags, and reduced-power, second-generation airbags were also mandated.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This was due to the injuries caused by first-generation airbags, though FMVSS 208 continues to require that bags be engineered and calibrated to be able to "save" the life of an *unbelted* 50th-percentile size and weight "male" crash test dummy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The technical performance and validation requirements for the inflator assembly used in airbag modules are specified in SAE USCAR 24–2.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some countries outside North America adhere to internationalized European ECE vehicle and equipment regulations rather than the United States Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] ECE airbags are generally smaller and inflate less forcefully than United States airbags because the ECE specifications are based on *belted* crash test dummies.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The Euro NCAP vehicle safety rating encourages manufacturers to take a comprehensive approach to occupant safety; a good rating can only be achieved by combining airbags with other safety features.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Almost every new car sold in Europe is equipped with front and side airbags, but in the European Union in 2020 and in the United Kingdom, and most other developed countries there is no direct legal requirement for new cars to feature airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Ecuador requires dual front airbags in new car models since 2013.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since January 2014, except for micro vehicles, all new cars made or imported in Argentina must have front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2014, all new cars sold in Brazil must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since July 2014, all new cars sold in Uruguay must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since December 2016, all new cars sold in Chile must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2017, all cars made or imported in Colombia must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2020, all new cars sold in Mexico must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] On 5 March 2021, the Indian Ministry of Road Transport and Highways mandated that all new vehicle models introduced in India after 1 April 2021 have dual front airbags; the regulation also requires that all existing models be equipped with dual front airbags by 31 August 2021.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] India also mandated that all passenger vehicles sold after October 2023 must have a minimum of six airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Inadvertent airbag deployment while a vehicle is being serviced can result in serious injury, and an improperly installed or defective airbag unit may fail to operate as intended.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] For this reason, individuals servicing vehicles, as well as first responders, are required to account for the fact that some airbag control systems may remain powered for up to 30 minutes after a vehicle's battery has been disconnected.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In some countries, the sale, transport, handling, and servicing of airbags and related components are subject to legal restrictions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In Germany, for example, airbags are regulated as hazardous explosive devices, and only trained auto mechanics are permitted to service airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Automaker policies regarding the service life of undeployed airbags vary.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Some manufacturers, such as Mercedes-Benz, have historically recommended replacement after a specified period to ensure reliability.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Certain Škoda vehicles have indicated an airbag service life of approximately 14 years from the date of manufacture, after which replacement may be uneconomical relative to the vehicle’s value.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] By contrast, Volvo has stated that airbags are designed to last for the lifetime of the vehicle, although this is not presented as an absolute guarantee of performance.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Although the millions of installed airbags in use have an excellent safety record, some limitations on their ability to protect car occupants exist.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The original implementation of front airbags did little to protect against side collisions, which can be more dangerous than frontal collisions because the protective crumple zone in front of the passenger compartment is completely bypassed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Side airbags and protective airbag curtains are increasingly being required in modern vehicles to protect against this very common category of collisions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Airbags are designed to deploy once only, so are ineffective if any further collisions occur after an initial impact.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Multiple impacts may occur during rollovers or other incidents involving multiple collisions, such as many multivehicle collisions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] An extremely dangerous situation occurs during "underride collisions", in which a passenger vehicle collides with the rear of a tractor-trailer lacking a rear underride guard, or hits the side of such a trailer not equipped with a side underride guard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] The platform bed of a typical trailer is roughly at the head height of a seated adult occupant of a typical passenger car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] This means not much of a barrier exists between a head and the edge of the trailer platform, except a glass windshield.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In an underride collision, the car's crush zones designed to absorb collision energy are completely bypassed, and the airbags may not deploy in time because the car does not decelerate appreciably until the windshield and roof pillars have already impacted the trailer bed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Even delayed inflation of airbags may be useless because of major intrusion into the passenger space, leaving occupants at high risk of major head trauma or decapitation in even low-speed collisions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Western European standards for underride guards have been stricter than North American standards, which typically have allowed grandfathering of older equipment that may still be on the road for decades.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Typical airbag systems are completely disabled by turning off the ignition key.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Unexpected turnoffs usually also disable the engine, power steering, and power brakes, and can be the direct cause of a collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] If a violent collision occurs, the disabled airbags will not deploy to protect vehicle occupants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] In 2014, General Motors admitted to concealing information about fatal collisions caused by defective ignition switches that would abruptly shut down a car (including its airbags).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p01] Between 13 and 74 deaths have been directly attributed to this defect, depending on how the fatalities are classified.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Under some rare conditions, airbags can injure and in some very rare instances kill vehicle occupants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] To provide crash protection for occupants not wearing seat belts, United States airbag designs trigger much more forcefully than airbags designed to the international ECE standards used in most other countries.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Recent "smart" airbag controllers can recognize if a seat belt is used, and alter the airbag cushion deployment parameters accordingly.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] In 1990, the first automotive fatality attributed to an airbag was reported.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] TRW produced the first gas-inflated airbag in 1994, with sensors and low inflation-force bags becoming common soon afterward.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Dual-depth (also known as dual-stage) airbags appeared on passenger cars in 1998.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] By 2005, deaths related to airbags had declined, with no adult deaths and two child deaths attributed to airbags that year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] However, injuries remain fairly common in collisions with airbag deployment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Serious injuries are less common, but severe or fatal injuries can occur to vehicle occupants very near an airbag or in direct contact when it deploys.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Such injuries may be sustained by unconscious drivers slumped over the steering wheel, unrestrained or improperly restrained occupants who slide forward in the seat during precrash braking, and properly belted drivers sitting very close to the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] A US study showed that the risk for a serious head injury occurring is 5.495% while travelling 40–48 km/h (25–30 mph).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The risk is reduced for passengers to 4.435%.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] This risk is lowered by 80.5% to 1.073% when using an airbag.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The risk for passengers is lowered by 82% to 0.797%.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The tests with the airbags were done at 56 km/h (35 mph), 8–16 km/h (5–10 mph) faster than the tests without air bags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] There is a 15.45% risk of serious injury to unprotected occupants at 48–56 km/h (30–35 mph), this drops to 4.68% with protected occupants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] This is a 69.7% decrease in change of serious injury, with the airbags deploying 96.1% of the time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Improvements in sensing and gas-generator technology have allowed the development of third-generation airbag systems that can adjust their deployment parameters to the size, weight, position, and restraint status of the occupant.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] These improvements have demonstrated a reduced injury risk factor for small adults and children, who had an increased risk of injury with first-generation airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] One model of airbags made by the Takata Corporation used ammonium nitrate–based gas-generating compositions in airbag inflators instead of the more stable, but more expensive compound tetrazole.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The ammonium nitrate-based inflators have a flaw where old inflators with long-term exposure to hot and humid climate conditions could rupture during deployment, projecting metal shards through the airbag and into the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] As of December 2022, the defect has caused 33 deaths worldwide, with up to 24 in the U.S. and the remaining in Australia and Malaysia.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) recalled over 33 million vehicles in May 2015, and fined Takata $70 million in November 2015.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Toyota, Mazda, and Honda have said that they will not use ammonium-nitrate inflators.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] In June 2017, Takata filed for bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] From 1990 to 2000, the United States NHTSA identified 175 fatalities caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] About 3.3 million airbag deployments have occurred during that interval, and the agency estimates more than 6,377 lives were saved and countless injuries were prevented.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] A rear-facing infant restraint put in the front seat of a vehicle places an infant's head close to the airbag, which can cause severe head injuries or death if the airbag deploys.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Some modern cars include a switch to disable the front-passenger airbag, in case a child-supporting seat is used there (although not in Australia, where rear-facing child seats are prohibited in the front where an airbag is fitted).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] In vehicles with side airbags, it is dangerous for occupants to lean against the windows, doors, and pillars, or to place objects between themselves and the side of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Articles hung from a vehicle's clothes hanger hooks can be hazardous if the vehicle's side-curtain airbags are deployed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] A seat-mounted airbag may also cause internal injury if the occupant leans against the door.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The aerospace industry and the United States government have applied airbag technologies for many years.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] NASA and United States Department of Defense have incorporated airbag systems in various aircraft and spacecraft applications as early as the 1960s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The first use of airbags for landing were Luna 9 and Luna 13.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] As with later missions, these would use the airbags to bounce along the surface, absorbing landing energy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The Mars Pathfinder lander employed an innovative airbag landing system, supplemented with aerobraking, parachute, and solid rocket landing thrusters.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] This prototype successfully tested the concept, and the two Mars Exploration Rover Mission landers employed similar landing systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The Beagle 2 Mars lander also tried to use airbags for landing; the landing was successful, and the lander touched down safely, but several of the spacecraft's solar panels failed to deploy, thereby disabling the spacecraft.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The Boeing Starliner uses six airbags to cushion the ground landing of the crewed capsule.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Airbags have also been used on military fixed-wing aircraft, such as the escape crew capsule of the F-111 Aardvark.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The United States Army has incorporated airbags in its UH-60A/L Black Hawk and OH-58D Kiowa Warrior helicopter fleets.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The Cockpit Air Bag System (CABS) consists of forward and lateral airbags, and an inflatable tubular structure (on the OH-58D only) with an Electronic Crash Sensor Unit (ECSU).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] The CABS system was developed by the United States Army Aviation Applied Technology Directorate, through a contract with Simula Safety Systems (now BAE Systems).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] It is the first conventional airbag system for occupant injury prevention (worldwide) designed and developed and placed in service for an aircraft, and the first specifically for helicopter applications.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] In the mid-1970s, the UK Transport Research Laboratory tested several types of motorcycle airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] In 2006 Honda introduced the first production motorcycle airbag safety system on its Gold Wing motorcycle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Honda claims that sensors in the front forks can detect a severe frontal collision and decide when to deploy the airbag, absorbing some of the forward energy of the rider and reducing the velocity at which the rider may be thrown from the motorcycle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] More commonly, air bag vests – either integrated into the motorcyclist's jacket or worn over it – have started to become used by regular riders on the street.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] MotoGP has made it compulsory since 2018 for riders to wear suits with integrated airbags.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Similarly, companies such as Helite and Hit-Air have commercialized equestrian airbags, which attach to the saddle and are worn by the rider.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/airbag-p02] Other sports, particularly skiing and snowboarding, have started introducing airbag safety mechanisms.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis was the son of Antonia and Sarantos Tremulis, Greek immigrants from a village near Sparta.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] In 1933, at 19 years old, Tremulis designed and helped build a radical custom Chevrolet for Chicago vaudeville comedian **Ralph Cook**.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] The car, with its long pointed hood and distinctive vertical grille resembling a church organ, was shown at the Century of Progress (Chicago World's Fair, 1933–1934).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Its futuristic lines and exaggerated proportions drew attention for being decades ahead of contemporary styling.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Among the visitors was designer Gordon Buehrig of Auburn-Cord-Duesenberg, who, impressed by Tremulis’ work, offered him a position on his design team.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] This project is often cited as the true beginning of Tremulis’ professional career in the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Among his other projects were the Cord 810 and 812 series, as well as a custom Duesenberg roadster with convertible and hardtop options.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] In 1936, he was named Chief Stylist for Auburn-Cord-Duesenberg and remained in that role until the company failed in 1937.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis briefly worked for General Motors before moving to Briggs-Le Baron, a custom coachbuilder for Chrysler at the time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] In 1938, he worked for Custom Motors in Beverly Hills, California, which made unique cars for movie stars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] He was also a consultant for Crosley and American Bantam in 1939.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] His designs for American Bantam remained in production until the firm switched entirely to the production of military Jeeps before World War II.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Returning to Briggs in 1939, he worked with Werner Gubitz and Howard "Dutch" Darrin to design the production versions of the Packard Clipper.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] He was also the creative source for the 1941 Chrysler "Thunderbolt" concept car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] His contributions to these two models helped establish styling trends that would influence automobile designs after World War II.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] After Pearl Harbor was bombed in 1941, Tremulis joined the United States Army Air Forces.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] He worked on advanced aircraft concepts at Wright Field (now Wright-Patterson Air Force Base) and developed an idea, which in the 1960s became known as the Boeing Dyna-Soar, a gliding re-entry space vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] While at the Air Corps, he made the first speculative drawings of what extraterrestrial life forms would use as transportation to visit the Earth.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] His concept drawings were the first saucer-shaped spacecraft drawings documented.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] After the War, Tremulis worked with the design firm of Tammen & Denison until Preston Tucker hired him to design the 1948 Tucker Sedan.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] As Phil Egan described in his book, "Design and Destiny: The Making of the Tucker Automobile", it was Tremulis who was primarily responsible for guiding the fabrication of the "Tin Goose" to conclusion.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] The first production Tucker automobiles were powered by a converted Franklin helicopter engine supplied by Air Cooled Motors.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Carl Doman, an engineer with Air Cooled, built a higher output engine, 275 horsepower (205 kW) versus 166 horsepower (168 PS), but was voted down by management, who felt the car was fast enough.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] The higher horsepower engine was for a future model called the Talisman, for which both Alex Tremulis and his assistant, Phil Egan, would eventually draw up proposals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] After his stint at Tucker, Tremulis worked briefly at Kaiser-Frazer under Arnot B.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] "Buzz" Grisinger, chief designer at Kaiser, who later become head of the Lincoln Design Studio at Ford, where Tremulis also worked starting in 1957.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] While at Ford Tremulis, a man who admired simplicity, was known for satirizing the gaudy 1958 Oldsmobile by drawing notes onto the 4 long horizontal trim strips on it's rear flanks, making it look rather like a musical staff.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] While at Kaiser-Frazer, he also worked with former Chrysler designer Herb Weissinger, whom he greatly admired for his sculptural design clay modeling skills.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] In 1957, as a Ford employee, Tremulis was assigned the task of designing the car that "he believed we would be driving in the year 2000".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis drew up plans and made a clay model of the Ford X-2000, a concept that would later be brought to life as a working prototype in 1999 by UK customizer Andy Saunders, who showed it at car shows in 1999 and 2000.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis designed the 1962 Ford Seattle-ite XXI concept car for the Seattle World's Fair.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis left Ford in 1963 to establish his consulting firm in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Among Tremulis' last designs was the 1978 Subaru BRAT.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis was a consultant for the 1988 film *Tucker: The Man and His Dream*, in which Elias Koteas portrayed him.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] Tremulis was also a frequent contributor to *Road & Track* magazine.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/alex-tremulis] He was buried at Ivy Lawn Memorial Park in Ventura, California.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] The **Automobile Racing Club of America** (**ARCA**) is an auto racing sanctioning body in the United States, founded in 1953 by John Marcum.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] A subsidiary of NASCAR since 2018, the current president of ARCA is Ron Drager, who took over the position in 1996 following the death of Bob Loga.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] The ARCA Menards Series races stock cars similar to those seen in past years in the NASCAR Cup Series, and indeed most cars used in the Menards Series were previously used in NASCAR.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA contains a mix of both professional racers and hobby racers alike, in addition to younger competitors trying to make a name for themselves, sometimes driving as part of a driver development program for a NASCAR team.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA Menards Series races are broadcast on Fox Sports 1, Fox Sports 2 or MAVTV, and they have been previously broadcast on ESPN, ESPN2, USA Network, TNN, Prime Network, CBS Sports Network, NBCSN, TBS, TNT, SpeedVision/Speed and Fox Sports Net.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA owns both the Toledo Speedway and Flat Rock Speedway.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA formerly sanctioned the ARCA Midget Series from 1988 until 2002 and a truck-racing series called the ARCA Lincoln Welders Truck Series from 1999 to 2016.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] John Marcum founded the Midwest Association for Race Cars (MARC) in 1953 as a regional stock car racing series after working as an official for NASCAR founder Bill France Sr.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] In 1964, the name was changed to the "Automobile Racing Club of America" when the series became national by racing on superspeedways.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] This ARCA is not to be confused with the organization founded in 1933 with the same name, which was the forerunner of the Sports Car Club of America (SCCA).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA started racing at Daytona International Speedway in 1964, during the Daytona Speedweeks, at the request of Bill France Sr., who had raced against Marcum in the 1940s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] The ARCA/NASCAR relationship continues today.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] The series frequently schedule events at the same track on the same weekend.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] The ARCA event is frequently the Saturday support race to the Sunday NASCAR Cup event.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] On April 27, 2018, NASCAR acquired ARCA.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] In 2019, it was announced that the NASCAR K&N Series East and West would be moved under the ARCA banner as the ARCA Menards Series East and ARCA Menards Series West for 2020.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] Former NASCAR drivers, such as Benny Parsons, Kyle Petty (who won the 1979 Daytona ARCA 200, the first race he ever competed in), Ken Schrader and others, have competed in and advanced through the ARCA series on the way to successful NASCAR careers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA has been used throughout its history as a stepping stone for hopeful NASCAR drivers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automobile-racing-club-of-america] ARCA uses a relatively simple point system to determine champions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Many emergency vehicles have distinctive lighting equipment to warn drivers of their presence.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Early road vehicles used fuelled lamps before the availability of electric lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The first Ford Model T used carbide lamps for headlights and oil lamps for tail lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] It did not have all-electric lighting as a standard feature until several years after its introduction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Dynamos for automobile headlights were first fitted around 1908 and became commonplace in 1920s automobiles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Trafficators—signalling arms that flipped up, which later were lighted—were introduced in the early 1900s, and were actuated either mechanically or pneumatically.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Tail lights and brake lights were introduced around 1915, and by 1919, low-beam or dipped beam headlights were available.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Sealed beam headlights were introduced in 1936 and standardized as the only acceptable type in the US in 1940.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Self-cancelling turn signals were developed in 1940.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] By 1945, headlights and signal lights were integrated into the body styling.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Halogen headlights were developed in Europe in 1960.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] High-intensity discharge (HID) headlights were produced starting in 1991.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] In 1993, the first LED tail lights were installed on mass-production automobiles, with LED headlights subsequently being introduced in the 2000s as more powerful LEDs became available.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The colour of light emitted by vehicle lights is largely standardized by established conventions, first codified in the 1949 Geneva Convention on Road Traffic and later specified in the 1968 United Nations Vienna Convention on Road Traffic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] With some regional exceptions, lights facing rearward must emit red light, side-facing lights and all turn signals must emit amber light, and lights facing forward must emit white or selective yellow light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] No other colours are permitted except on emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Vehicle lighting colour specifications can differ somewhat in countries that have not signed the 1949 and/or 1968 Conventions; examples include turn signals and side marker lights in North America, as described in those lights' sections later in this article.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Forward illumination is provided by high- ("main", "full", "driving") and low- ("dip", "dipped", "passing") beam headlights, which may be augmented by auxiliary fog lights, driving lights, or cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Low beam (also called dipped beam, passing beam, or meeting beam) headlights provide adequate forward and lateral illumination without dazzling other road users with excessive glare.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] This beam is specified for use whenever other vehicles are present ahead.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE regulations for dipped beam headlights specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is flat and low, while the half of the beam closest to the outside of the road slopes up and towards the near side of the roadway.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] This permits a functional compromise where it is possible to substantially prevent glare for oncoming drivers, while still allowing adequate illumination for drivers to see pedestrians, road signs, hazards, etc. on their side of the road.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The United States and Canada use proprietary FMVSS / CMVSS standards instead of UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] These standards contain regulations for dipped beam headlights that also specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is also flat and low, but not as low as prescribed in UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The half of the beam closest to the outside of the road is also flat, but higher than the half closest to oncoming vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] This results in substantially increased glare for oncoming drivers and also poorer illumination of the near side of the roadway in comparison to headlights conforming to UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] High beam (also called main beam, driving beam, or full beam) headlights provide an intense, centre-weighted distribution of light with no particular glare control.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Therefore, they are only suitable for use when alone on the road, as the glare they produce will dazzle other drivers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE Regulations permit higher-intensity high-beam headlights than allowed under U.S. and Canadian FMVSS / CMVSS standards.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Auxiliary high beam lights may be fitted to provide high-intensity light to enable the driver to see at longer range than the vehicle's high beam headlights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Such lights are most notably fitted on rally cars, and are occasionally fitted to production vehicles derived from or imitating such cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] They are common in countries with large stretches of unlit roads, or in regions such as the Nordic countries that receive fewer daylight hours during winter.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] "Driving light" is a term hailing from the early days of night time driving, when it was relatively rare to encounter an opposing vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Only on occasions when opposing drivers passed each other would the low (dipped or "passing") beam be used.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The high beam was therefore known as the "driving beam", and this terminology is still found in international UN Regulations, which do not distinguish between a vehicle's primary (mandatory) and auxiliary (optional) upper/driving beam lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The "driving light" term has been supplanted in US regulations by the functionally descriptive term "auxiliary high-beam light".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Many countries regulate the installation and use of driving lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] For example, in Russia, each vehicle may have no more than three pairs of driving lights (including the original lights), and in Paraguay, auxiliary driving lights must be off and covered with opaque material when the vehicle is operated in urban areas.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Front fog lights provide a wide, bar-shaped beam of light with a sharp cutoff at the top, and are generally aimed and mounted low.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] They may produce white or selective yellow light, and were designed for use at low speed to increase the illumination directed towards the road surface and verges in conditions of poor visibility due to fog, dust or snow.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] They are sometimes used in place of dipped-beam headlights, reducing glare from fog or falling snow, although the legality of using front fog lights without low-beam headlights varies by jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] In most countries, weather conditions rarely necessitate the use of front fog lights and there is no legal requirement for them, so their primary purpose is frequently cosmetic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] They are often available as optional extras or only on higher trim levels of many cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Since as early as the 2020s, several car manufacturers have noticeably omitted the front fog lights from many of their latest models, as more recent high-tech lighting technologies such as daytime running lamps (DRLs) and LEDs connected to automatic high-beam systems negate the use of fog lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] However, some manufacturers who still offer fog lights as standard equipment in certain model trims have diversified its use to function also as an automatic lighting delay for vehicles, to light up surroundings and roadside curbs after being parked.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] An SAE study has shown that in the United States, more people inappropriately use their fog lights in dry weather than use them properly in poor weather.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] The respective purposes of front fog lights and driving lights are often confused, due in part to the misconception that fog lights are always selective yellow, while any auxiliary light that makes white light is a driving light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Automakers and aftermarket parts and accessories suppliers frequently refer interchangeably to "fog lights" and "driving lights" (or "fog/driving lights").
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] On some models, cornering lights provide steady-intensity white light for lateral illumination in the direction of an intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] They are generally actuated in conjunction with the turn signals, and they may be wired to also illuminate when the vehicle is shifted into reverse gear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Some modern vehicles activate the cornering light on one or the other side when the steering wheel input reaches a predetermined angle in that direction, regardless of whether a turn signal has been activated.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] American technical standards contain provisions for front cornering lights as well as rear cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Cornering lights have traditionally been prohibited under international UN Regulations, though provisions have recently been made to allow them as long as they are only operable when the vehicle is travelling at less than 40 kilometres per hour (about 25 mph).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p01] Police cars, emergency vehicles, and vehicles competing in road rallies are sometimes equipped with an auxiliary spotlight, sometimes called an "alley light", in a swivel-mounted housing attached to one or both A-pillars, aimed by a handle protruding through the pillar into the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity devices are lights and reflectors that are intended to make a vehicle more conspicuous and visible with respect to its presence, position, direction of travel, change in direction, or deceleration.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Such lights may light steadily, blink, or flash, depending on their intended and regulated function.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Most must be fitted in pairs—one left and one right—though some vehicles have multiple pairs (such as two left and two right stop lights) and/or redundant light sources (such as one left and one right stop light, each containing two bulbs).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Front position lights (known as parking lights in North America and front sidelights in the UK) provide nighttime standing-vehicle conspicuity.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They are designed to use little electricity so they can be left on when parked for prolonged periods of time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Despite the UK term, these are not the same as the side marker lights described below.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The front position lights on any vehicle must emit white light, with the exception of motorcycles, which may have amber front position lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, Canada, Mexico, Iceland, Japan, New Zealand, and Australia (only if combined with a side marker), South Korea, North Korea, Vietnam, China, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, and much of the Middle East, they may emit amber light on any vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The "city light" terminology for front position lights derives from the practice, formerly adhered to in cities like Moscow, London and Paris, of driving at night in urban areas using these low-intensity lights rather than the vehicle's headlights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In Germany, the StVZO (Road Traffic Licensing Regulations) calls for a different function provided by these lights: with the vehicle's ignition switched off, the operator may activate a low-intensity white light at the front and red light at the rear on either the left or right side.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This function is used when parking in narrow unlit streets to provide parked-vehicle conspicuity to approaching drivers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This function, which is optional under UN and US regulations, is served passively in the United States by mandatory side marker retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some countries permit or require vehicles to be equipped with daytime running lights (DRLs).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the regulations of the country for which the vehicle is built, these may be functionally dedicated lights, or the function may be provided by the low beam or high beam headlights, the front turn signals, or the front fog lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Passenger cars and small delivery vans first type approved to UN Regulation 48 on or after 7 February 2011, and large vehicles (trucks and buses) type approved since August 2012, must be equipped with DRLs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Functional piggybacking, such as using the headlights, front turn signals, or fog lights as DRLs, is not permitted; the EU Directive requires functionally specific daytime running lights compliant with UN Regulation 87 and mounted to the vehicle in accord with UN Regulation 48.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Prior to the DRL mandate, countries requiring daytime lights permitted low beam headlights to provide that function.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] National regulations in Canada, Sweden, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Iceland, and Denmark require hardwired automatic DRL systems of varying specification.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] DRLs are permitted in many countries where they are not required, but prohibited in other countries not requiring them.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Front, side, and rear position lights are permitted, required, or forbidden to illuminate in combination with daytime running lights, depending on the jurisdiction and the DRL implementation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Likewise, according to jurisdictional regulations, DRLs mounted within a certain distance of turn signals are permitted or required to extinguish or dim down to parking light intensity individually when the adjacent turn signal is operating.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 87 stipulates that DRLs must emit white light with an intensity of at least 400 candela on axis and no more than 1200 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, daytime running lights may emit either amber or white light, and may produce up to 7,000 candela.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This has provoked a large number of complaints about glare.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] UK regulations briefly required vehicles first used on or after 1 April 1987 to be equipped with a "dim-dip" device or special low-intensity running lights, except such vehicles as complying fully with UN Regulation 48 regarding the installation of lighting equipment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] A dim-dip device operates the dipped beam headlights at between 10% and 20% of normal low-beam intensity.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Running lights permitted as an alternative to dim-dip were required to emit at least 200 candela straight ahead, and no more than 800 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In practice, most vehicles were equipped with the dim-dip option rather than dedicated running lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The dim-dip systems were not intended for daytime use as DRLs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather, they operated if the engine was running *and* the driver switched on the position lights (called sidelights in the UK).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The UK was the only country to require such dim-dip systems, though vehicles so equipped were sold in other Commonwealth countries with left-hand traffic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1988, the European Commission successfully prosecuted the UK government in the European Court of Justice, arguing that the UK requirement for dim-dip was illegal under EC directives prohibiting member states from enacting vehicle lighting requirements not contained in pan-European EC directives.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] As a result, the UK requirement for dim-dip was quashed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Nevertheless, dim-dip systems remain permitted, and while such systems are not presently as common as they once were, dim-dip functionality was fitted on many new cars well into the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States, amber front and red rear side marker lights and retroreflectors are required.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The law initially required lights *or* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1968.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This was amended to require lights *and* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1970.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These side-facing devices make the vehicle's presence, position and direction of travel clearly visible from oblique angles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The lights are wired to illuminate whenever the vehicles' parking lights and tail lights are on, including when the headlights are being used.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Front amber side markers in the United States may be wired to flash in synchronous phase or opposite-phase with the turn signals; nevertheless, they are not required to flash at all.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Side markers are permitted but not required on cars and light passenger vehicles outside the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These were sometimes used in tandem with fender lights during the same time period, when fenders were separate from the body and only covered the wheels.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They are activated by the driver on one side of the vehicle at a time to advertise intent to turn or change lanes towards that side, or used simultaneously as a hazard warning signal to warn other drivers of a vehicle parked on the road (see below).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] For many years, turn signals' on-off operation was activated by a thermal flasher unit which used a heating element, leaf spring, and a bimetallic strip.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] When activated by the stalk switch on the steering column, the signal lights and heating element turned on.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The heat caused the bimetallic strip to bend such that it threw the leaf spring over centre, opening the circuit and breaking power to the heating element and the signal lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] When the bimetallic strip cooled down, it would pull the leaf spring back over centre in the other direction, closing the contacts and again sending power to the lights and heating element.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The cycle would repeat until the power to the thermal flasher was switched off by the stalk switch.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Thermal flashers gradually gave way to electromechanical relays; one of many control strategies with relay-type flashers is to use a relaxation oscillator chip to generate square waves to the relay coil, causing the relay contacts to open and close.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern cars now use a relaxation oscillator and solid-state relay built into the body control module to flash the lights, and use speakers to produce the distinctive clicking sound associated with turn signals, which was previously made by a relay or the leaf spring in a thermal flasher.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] If the stalk switch is not moved beyond the fixed left/right position and allowed to flip back, the control module will only flash the lights three times.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Electric turn signal lights date from as early as 1907.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1908, Alfredo Barrachini in Rome added electric lights inside the arms that turned on as they extended, but operation was still by a cable system.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] An early patent for a new style of turn signal was issued in 1909 to a British man named Percy Douglas-Hamilton, who came up with a system that used a hand on each side of the car, which could be illuminated to indicate a coming turn.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Silent film star Florence Lawrence is also credited with introducing an innovative version of the signalling arm in 1914, a predecessor to the modern turn signal, and a mechanical brake signal.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] She did not patent these inventions, however, and received no credit or profit from them.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Possibly the first factory installation of illuminated turn signals was on the Talbot 105 (as well as the 75 and 95), which used them at the front as well as at the rear from 1932 until 1935.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The modern flashing turn signal was patented in 1938, and shortly after, most major automobile manufacturers offered this optional feature before it became mandatory in 1967.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] As of 2013, most countries require turn signals on all new vehicles that are driven on public roadways.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Alternative systems of hand signals were used earlier and remain common for bicycles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Hand signals are also sometimes used when regular vehicle lights are malfunctioning or for older vehicles without turn signals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some cars from about 1900 to through 1966 used retractable semaphores called trafficators rather than flashing lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They were commonly mounted high up behind the front doors and swung out to a horizontal position.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They were fragile and could be easily broken off, and also had a tendency to stick in the closed or open position.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They could be fitted with a fixed or flashing light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] After turn signals were introduced regulations were brought in requiring them and laying out specifications that had to be met.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In most countries, cars must be equipped with side-mounted turn signal repeaters to make the turn indication visible laterally (i.e. to the sides of the vehicle) rather than just to the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These are permitted, but not required in the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] As an alternative in both the United States and Canada, the front amber side marker lights may be wired to flash with the turn signals, but this is not mandatory.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Mercedes-Benz introduced side turn signal repeaters integrated into the side-view mirrors in 1998, starting with its facelifted E-Class (W210).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Since then, many automakers have been incorporating side turn signal devices into the mirror housings rather than mounting them on the vehicle's fenders.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some evidence suggests that mirror-mounted turn signals may be more effective than fender-mounted ones.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are required to blink on and off, or "flash", at a steady rate of between 60 and 120 pulses per minute (1–2 Hz).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations require that all turn signals flash in simultaneous phase; US regulations permit side marker lights wired for side turn signal functionality to flash in opposite-phase.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] An audio and/or visual tell-tale indicator is required, to advise the driver when the turn signals are activated and operating.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This usually takes the form of one green light on the dashboard on cars from the 1950s or older, or two green indicator lights on cars from the 1960s to the present, and a rhythmic ticking sound generated electromechanically or electronically by the flasher.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] It is also required that the vehicle operator be alerted by much faster- or slower-than-normal flashing in the event a turn signal light fails.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are, in almost every case, activated by a horizontal stalk protruding from the side of the steering column, though on some vehicles it protrudes from the dashboard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The driver raises or lowers the outboard end of the stalk in accord with the clockwise or anticlockwise direction the steering wheel is about to be turned.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In left-hand drive vehicles, the turn indicator stalk is usually located to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In right-hand-drive vehicles, there is less consistency; it may be located to the left or to the right of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations do not specify a mandatory location for the turn signal control, only that it be visible and operable by the driver, and—at least in North America—that it be labelled with a specific symbol if it is not located on the left side of the steering column.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The international UN Regulations do not include analogous specifications.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Virtually all vehicles (except many motorcycles and commercial semi-tractors) have a turn indicator self-cancelling feature that returns the lever to the neutral (no signal) position as the steering wheel approaches the straight-ahead position after a turn has been made.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Beginning in the late 1960s, using the direction-indicator lights to signal for a lane change was facilitated by the addition of a spring-loaded momentary signal-on position just shy of the left and right detents.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The signal operates for however long the driver holds the lever partway towards the left or right turn signal detent.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have an automatic lane-change indication feature; tapping the lever partway towards the left or right signal position and immediately releasing it causes the applicable turn indicators to flash three to five times.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some transit buses, such as those in New York, have turn signals activated by floor-mounted momentary-contact footswitches on the floor near the driver's left foot (on left-hand drive buses).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The foot-activated signals allow bus drivers to keep both hands on the steering wheel while watching the road and scanning for passengers as they approach a bus stop.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] New York City Transit bus drivers, among others, are trained to step continuously on the right directional switch while servicing a bus stop, to signal other road users they are intentionally dwelling at the stop, allowing following buses to skip that stop.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This method of signalling requires no special arrangements for self-cancellation or passing.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Sequential turn signals are a feature on some cars, wherein the turn signal function is provided by multiple lit elements that illuminate sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The visual effect is one of outward motion in the direction of the intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The earlier, fitted to the 1965 through 1968 Ford-built cars and the 1971–1972 Nissan Cedric, employed an electric motor driving, through reduction gearing, a set of three slow-turning cams.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These cams would actuate switches to turn on the lights in sequence.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Later Ford cars and the 1969 Imperial used a transistorised control module with no moving parts to wear, break, or go out of adjustment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] FMVSS 108 has been officially interpreted as requiring all light sources in an active turn signal to illuminate simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles, such as the 2010 and later Ford Mustang, are designed such that the first lit segment of the multi-unit light is considered as the official turn signal, with the segments illuminated afterward considered as auxiliary lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Other US vehicles with sequential turn signals comply by illuminating all elements of the turn signal simultaneously, before sequentially turning them off.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Until the early 1960s, most front turn signals worldwide emitted white light and most rear turn signals emitted red light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Currently, most countries outside the United States and Canada require that all front, side and rear turn signals produce amber light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In Belgium, Brazil, Canada, the GCC countries, Israel, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the US, the rear signals may be amber or red.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Additionally, red turn signals can also be found in countries with trade agreements with the US such as Mexico and South Korea, and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of red rear turn signals have claimed that they are less costly to manufacture, and automakers use the turn signal colour as a styling element to differentiate vehicles of different model years.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of amber rear turn signals say they are more easily discernible as turn signals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] It has been recognised since the 1960s that amber turn signals are more quickly spotted than red ones.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] There is some evidence that turn signals with colourless clear lenses and amber bulbs may be less conspicuous in bright sunlight than those with amber lenses and colourless bulbs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The amber bulbs commonly used in turn signals with colourless lenses are no longer made with cadmium glass, since various regulations worldwide, including the European RoHS directive, banned cadmium because of its toxicity.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Amber glass made without cadmium is relatively costly, so most amber bulbs are now made with clear glass dipped in an amber coating.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] With accumulated heat-cool cycles, though, some of these coatings may flake off the bulb glass, or the colour may fade.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This causes the turn signal to emit white light rather than the required amber light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The international regulation on motor vehicle bulbs requires manufacturers to test bulbs for colour endurance.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] However, no test protocol or colour durability requirement is specified.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Discussion is ongoing within the *Groupe des Rapporteurs d'Éclairage*, the UNECE working group on vehicular lighting regulation, to develop and implement a colour durability standard.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather than using an amber bulb, some signal lights contain an inner amber plastic enclosure between a colourless bulb and the colourless outer lens or by using integrated amber LEDs in a colourless enclosure which produces less heat.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity for the rear of a vehicle is provided by rear position lights (also called tail lights).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These are required to produce only red light and to be wired such that they are lit whenever the front position lights are lit, including when the headlights are on.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear position lights may be combined with the vehicle's stop lights or be separate from them.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In combined-function installations, the lights produce brighter red light as stop lights and dimmer red light as rear position lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide stipulate minimum intensity ratios between the bright (stop) and dim (position) modes, so that a vehicle displaying rear position lights will not be mistakenly interpreted as showing stop lights and vice versa.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Red steadily lit rear lights, brighter than the rear position lights, are activated when the driver applies the vehicle's brakes and warn vehicles behind to prepare to stop.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These are formally called "stop lamps" in technical standards and regulations and in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic, though they are often informally called brake lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They are required to be fitted in multiples of two, symmetrically at the left and right edges of the rear of every vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] 7 specify a range of acceptable intensity for a stop light of 60 to 185 candela.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where the UN regulations are not recognised, the acceptable range for a single-compartment stop light is 80 to 300 candela.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and Canada since 1986, in Australia and New Zealand since 1990, and in Europe and other countries applying UN Regulation 48 since 1998, a central stop (brake) light mounted higher than the vehicle's left and right stop lights is also required.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The so-called "centre high mount stop lamp", or **CHMSL** (pronounced /ˈtʃɪmzəl/), is sometimes informally called the "centre brake light", the "third brake light", the "eye-level brake light", the "safety brake light", or the "high-level brake light".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL may use one or more filament bulbs or LEDs, or a strip of neon tubing as its light source.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is intended to provide a warning to drivers whose view of the vehicle's left and right stop lights is blocked by interceding vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] It also provides a redundant stop light signal in the event of a stop light malfunction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where rear turn signals are permitted to emit red light, the CHMSL also helps to differentiate brake lights from rear position lights and turn signal lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] On passenger cars, the CHMSL may be placed above the back glass, affixed to the vehicle's interior just inside the back glass, or integrated into the vehicle's deck lid or into a spoiler.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Other specialised fitments are sometimes seen; the Jeep Wrangler and Land Rover Freelander have the CHMSL on a stalk fixed to the spare wheel carrier.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Trucks, vans, and commercial vehicles sometimes have the CHMSL mounted to the trailing edge of the vehicle's roof.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is required by regulations worldwide to be centred laterally on the vehicle, though UN Regulation 48 permits lateral offset of up to 15 cm if the vehicle's lateral centre is not coincident with a fixed body panel, but instead separates movable components such as doors.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Such an offset can be seen on the third-generation Renault Master and first-generation Ford Transit Connect vans.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The height of the CHMSL is also regulated, both in absolute terms and with respect to the mounting height of the vehicle's conventional left and right stop lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the left and right lights' height, the lower edge of the CHMSL may be just above the left and right lights' upper edge.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1952 Volkswagen Bus was equipped with only one stop light, mounted centrally and higher than the left and right rear lights, which did not produce a stop light function.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1968–1971 Ford Thunderbird could be ordered with optional supplemental high-mounted stop and turn signal lights integrated into the left and right interior trim surrounding the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The Oldsmobile Toronado (from 1971 to 1978) and the Buick Riviera (from 1974 to 1976) had similar dual high-mounted supplemental stop/turn lights as standard equipment; these were located on the outside of the vehicle below the bottom of the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of configuration was not widely adopted at the time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Car and lighting manufacturers in Germany experimented with dual high-mount supplemental stop lights in the early 1980s, but this effort, too, failed to gain wide popular or regulatory support.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Effective with the 1986 model year, the United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada mandated that all new passenger cars come equipped with a CHMSL.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The requirement was extended to light trucks and vans for the 1994 model year.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Early studies involving taxicabs and other fleet vehicles found that a third high-level stop light reduced rear-end collisions by about 50%.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Once the novelty effect wore off as most vehicles on the road came to be equipped with a CHMSL, the crash-avoidance benefit declined.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] However, said benefit has not declined to zero, and a CHMSL has become so inexpensive to incorporate into a vehicle that it remains a cost-effective collision avoidance feature even at the long-term enduring crash-reduction benefit of 4.3%.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] A NHTSA report suggests that a vehicle equipped with a CHMSL has 23.7% less risk to be involved as a lead vehicle in a chain collision and 16.0% less risk to be involved as a middle vehicle in such a collision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency stop signalling is a lighting function wherein the vehicle's stop (brake) lights and/or hazard/turn indicators flash in phase at 3 to 5 Hz under heavy or urgent braking.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The emergency stop signal is automatically activated if the vehicle speed is greater than 50 km/h (31 mph) and the emergency braking logic defined by regulation No.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In February 2019, members of the European Parliament approved rules making emergency stop signals mandatory on new vehicles sold in the European Union.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Toyota, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and BMW were among the earlier automakers to begin equipping vehicles with ESS.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2013, Kia introduced the concept on some of their Australian-market models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Other methods of severe braking indication have also been implemented; some Volvo models make the stop lights brighter, and some BMWs have "Adaptive Brake Lights" that effectively increase the size of the stop lights under severe braking by illuminating them at brighter-than-normal intensity.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] As long as the brighter-than-normal stop lights are within the regulated maximum intensity for stop lights in general, this kind of implementation does not require specific regulatory approval, since the stop lights continue to operate in accord with general stop light regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The idea behind such emergency braking indicator systems is to catch following drivers' attention with increased urgency.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] However, there remains considerable debate over whether the system offers a measurable increase in safety.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] To date, studies of vehicles with ESS have not shown significant improvement.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and Mercedes differ not only in operational mode (growing vs. intensifying vs. flashing, respectively), but also in such parameters as the deceleration threshold of activation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Data is being collected and analyzed in an effort to determine how such a system might be implemented to maximize a safety benefit, if such a benefit can be realized with visual emergency braking displays.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] An experimental study at the University of Toronto has tested stop lights which gradually and continuously grow in illuminated area with increasing braking.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The ESS is not expensive because it reuses existing warning and stop signals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] One potential problem with flashing stop lights in the United States and Canada is regulations that permit flashing stop lights to be used as rear turn signal and hazard lights, in lieu of separate dedicated lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In Europe and other countries adhering to UN Regulation 48, vehicles must be equipped with one or two bright red "rear fog lamps", which serve as high-intensity rear position lights to be activated in poor visibility conditions to make the vehicle more visible from the rear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The allowable range of intensity for a rear fog light is 150 to 300 candela, within the range of a US stop light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear fog lights are not required equipment in the US, but they are permitted, and they are found almost exclusively on European-brand vehicles in North America.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Audi, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, Mini, Land Rover, Porsche, Saab, and Volvo provide functional rear fog lights on their North American models.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles from non-European brands which are adaptions of European-market offerings, such as the first-generation Ford Transit Connect, have come standard with rear fog lights, or vehicles with European-market counterparts, such as the second generation Chrysler 300, have an option for them.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The second generation Oldsmobile Aurora also had dual rear fog lights installed in the rear bumper as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Most jurisdictions permit rear fog lights to be installed either singly or in pairs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] If a single rear fog is fitted, most jurisdictions require it to be located at or to the driver's side of the vehicle's centreline—whichever side is the prevailing driver's side in the country in which the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This is to maximise the sight line of following drivers to the rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In many cases, a single reversing light is mounted on the passenger side of the vehicle, positionally symmetrical with the rear fog.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] If two rear fog lights are fitted, they must be symmetrical with respect to the vehicle's centreline.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of twin rear fog lights say two lights provide vehicle distance information not available from a single light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of the single rear fog light say dual rear fog lights closely mimic the appearance of illuminated stop lights (which are mandatorily installed in pairs), reducing the conspicuity of the stop lights' message when the rear fogs are activated.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] To provide some safeguard against rear fog lights being confused with stop lights, UN Regulation 48 requires a separation of at least 10 cm between the closest illuminated edges of any stop light and any rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] To warn adjacent vehicle operators and pedestrians of a vehicle's rearward motion, and to provide illumination to the rear when reversing, each vehicle must be equipped with one or two rear-mounted, rear-facing reversing (or "backup") lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Reversing lights are required to produce white light by US and international UN regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] However, some countries have at various times permitted amber reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, for example, vehicle manufacturers were faced with the task of localizing American cars originally equipped with combination red brake/turn signal lights and white reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Both countries now require white reversing lights, and the combination amber turn/reverse light is no longer permitted on new vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The US state of Washington currently permits reversing lights to emit white or amber light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some car models, such as some Saabs have white reversing lights in the front turn indicators that switch on with the rear reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The rear registration plate is illuminated either by a single or a pair of yellow or white light(s), affixed within the indentation of the trunk or bumper.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] It is designed to light the surface of the plate without creating light directly visible to the rear of the vehicle, and must be illuminated whenever the position lights are lit.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Large vehicles such as trucks and buses are in many cases required to carry additional lighting devices beyond those required on passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The specific requirements vary according to the regulations in force where the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US and Canada, vehicles over 80 inches (2.032 m) wide must be equipped with three amber front and three red rear identification lights spaced 6–12 inches (15–30 cm) apart at the centre of the front and rear of the vehicle, as high as practicable.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The front identification lights are typically mounted atop the cab of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The purpose of these lights is to alert other drivers to the presence of a wide (and usually tall) vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 48 requires vehicles exceeding 2.10 metres (83 in) in width to be equipped with white front and red rear end-outline marker lights on both the left and right, which, like North American identification lights, are intended to indicate a vehicle's overall width and height.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The front clearance lights may be amber in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] US and Canadian regulations require large vehicles to be equipped with amber side marker lights and reflectors mounted midway between the front and rear side markers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Australian Design Rule 45/01 provides for side marker lights on trucks and other large vehicles producing amber light to the front and red to the rear with no requirement to emit light to the side.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Until about the 1970s in France, Spain, Morocco, and possibly other countries, many commercial vehicles and some Soviet Sovtransavto road trains had a green light mounted on the rear offside.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This could be operated by the driver to indicate that it was safe for the following vehicle to overtake.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The hazard warning signal (sometimes called "hazard warning flashers", "hazard warning lights", "emergency lights", "4-way flashers", "hazards", or "flashers") is provided by flashing all of a vehicle's left and right turn signals simultaneously and in phase.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Hazard warning signals first appeared as aftermarket accessories in the early 1950s; by the late 1960s, regulations around the world came to require all new vehicles to be so equipped.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Operation of the warning signals must be from a control independent of the turn signal control, and an audiovisual tell-tale must be provided to the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In most vehicles, the hazard warning signals can be switched on and off with a physical push-button, which is typically marked with a triangular symbol, symbolizing a warning triangle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with separate left and right green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, both left and right indicators may flash to provide a visual indication of the hazard flashers' operation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with a single green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, a separate red tell-tale must be provided for hazard flasher indication.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Because the hazard flasher function operates the vehicle's left and right turn signals, a left or a right turn signal function may not be provided while the hazard flashers are operating.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Apart from its use as emergency lighting, a single flash of the hazard lights is used to show gratitude to yielding drivers in several countries.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] However, in the United Kingdom, they must not be used except to warn others of either a temporary obstruction when the vehicle is stationary or a hazard ahead on a dual carriageway with a speed limit of at least 50 mph.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] "Retroreflectors" (also called "reflex reflectors") produce no light of their own, but rather reflect incident light towards its source, such as another driver's headlights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They are regulated as automotive lighting devices, and specified to account for the separation between a vehicle's headlights and its driver's eyes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Thus, vehicles can remain conspicuous even with their lights off.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide require all vehicles and trailers to be equipped with rear-facing red retroreflectors; in countries where UN Regulation No.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] 48 is applied, these must be triangular on trailers and non-triangular on vehicles other than trailers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Since 1968, US regulations also require side-facing retroreflectors, amber in front and red in the rear.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Sweden, South Africa, and other countries have at various times required white front-facing retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations explicitly permit vehicle signal lights with intensity automatically increased during bright daylight hours when sunlight reduces the effectiveness of the stop lights, and automatically decreased during hours of darkness when glare could be a concern.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations in the US and by the UN contain provisions for determining the minimum and maximum acceptable intensity for lights that contain more than a single light source.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some jurisdictions, such as the US states of Washington, Oregon and Idaho, permit vehicles to be equipped with auxiliary rear signal systems displaying a green light when the accelerator is depressed, yellow light when the vehicle is coasting, and red light when the brake is depressed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Such systems have in the past been sold as aftermarket accessories, but are today seldom seen in traffic.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Since the late 1960s, there have been proposals to introduce a front-mounted brake light, where green or blue lights would indicate to pedestrians at crossings that an approaching vehicle is slowing down.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] A small subjective survey was undertaken in the US in 1971.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2014, the idea was suggested by Slovak Lubomír Marjak (of manufacturing company Lumaco, which makes front brake lights) to German EU parliamentarian Dieter-Lebrecht Koch.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Field tests were done in Germany in 2017, as well as in Slovakia in 2022 and 2023.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Expert analysts have found severe flaws in these tests and the accompanying safety claims.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The only production car to feature a built-in front brake light (as of 2023) was the Bricklin SV-1 of 1974.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, among other bodies, has commissioned studies of vehicle signal systems and configurations to determine the most promising avenues and best practices for enhanced crash avoidance via optimized vehicle conspicuity and signal lighting systems.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Most cars have at least one "dome light" (or "courtesy light") located in or near the ceiling of the passenger compartment, to provide illumination by which to fasten seatbelts and enter or exit the car.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These often have an option to automatically switch on when the front (or any) passenger doors are opened.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Many vehicles have expanded this feature, causing the overhead interior light to remain on after all doors are closed, allowing passengers to fasten seat belts with added illumination.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The extended lighting cycle usually ends when the vehicle's ignition has begun, or a gradual reduction in light emitted after a couple of minutes if the car is not started, called "theater" lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Interior lighting has been added on some vehicles at the bottom edge of the dashboard, illuminating the floor for front passengers, or underneath the front seats at the rear, illuminating the floor for rear passengers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of convenience lighting approach is also sometimes used to illuminate interior or exterior door handles, exterior step running boards, or electric window switches.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] LED light sources appear increasingly as interior convenience lights in various locations, especially with finely focused lighting on console control surfaces and in cabin storage areas.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Map lights are aimed at specific passenger positions and allow for reading without glare distraction to the driver.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have "approach lighting" or "puddle lights" (lights that illuminate the ground outside the doors) in the exterior mirrors or lower edges of the doors, as well as interior lighting activated via key fob.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Many cars have lights in the trunk, the engine compartment, the glove box, and other storage compartments.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern pickup trucks usually have one or more white cargo lights that illuminate the bed of the truck, often controlled in conjunction with the interior dome lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Most gauges and controls on a dashboard in modern vehicles are illuminated when the headlights are turned on, and the intensity of light can be adjusted by the driver for comfort.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Saab automobiles, for example, have an aircraft-style "night panel" function that shuts off all interior illumination save for the speedometer (unless attention is called to a critical situation on another gauge) to improve the driver's night vision.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency vehicles such as fire engines, ambulances, police cars, snow-removal vehicles and tow trucks are usually equipped with intense warning lights of particular colours.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] These may be motorised rotating beacons, xenon strobes, or arrays of LEDs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] The prescribed colours differ by jurisdiction; in most countries, blue and red special warning lights are used on police, fire, and medical-emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and some other jurisdictions, amber lights are for tow trucks, private security personnel, construction vehicles, and other nonofficial special-service vehicles, while volunteer firefighters use red, blue, or green, depending on jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US it is a violation of the DOT (Department of Transportation) Uniform Vehicle Code for any non-emergency vehicle (Police/Fire/Ambulance) to operate forward-facing red lights of any kind.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Some US states allow emergency vehicles to have blue lights that can be turned on to warn drivers of an emergency vehicle in action; blue and red lights can be combined, forward- and/or rear-facing.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] In the UK, doctors may use green warning lights; although these do not allow the user to claim any exemption from road traffic regulations (compared to the blue lights used by statutory emergency services when responding to calls).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Special warning lights, usually amber, are also sometimes mounted on slow or wide vehicles such as mobile cranes, excavators, tractors, and even mobility scooters in certain conditions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Standard taxicabs for street hire are distinguished by special lights affixed to the vehicle's roof in accordance with local regulations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] They may have an illuminated "Taxi" sign, a light to signal that they are ready to take passengers, or off duty, or an emergency panic light the driver can activate in the event of a robbery to alert passersby to call the police.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on local regulations, the "Taxi" sign may also be required to display a number identifying the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The incandescent light bulb was for a long time the only light source used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Incandescent bulbs are still commonly used in turn signals to stop hyper-flashing of the turn signal flashers.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Standardized type numbers are used by manufacturers to identify bulbs with the same specifications.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Bases may be bayonet-type with one or two contacts, plastic or glass wedges, or dual wire loops or ferrules used on tubular "festoon" lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Screw-base lights are never used in automobile applications due to their loosening under vibration.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Signal lights with internal or external coloured lenses use colourless bulbs; conversely, lights with colourless lenses may use red or amber bulbs to provide light of the required colours for the various functions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Tungsten-halogen lights are a very common light source for headlights and other forward illumination functions.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Some recent vehicles use small halogen bulbs for exterior signalling and marking functions, as well.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The first halogen light approved for automotive use was the H1, which used 55 watts producing 1500 lumens and was introduced in Europe in 1962.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Since 1993, light-emitting diodes (LEDs) have increasingly been used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] They offer a very long service life, extreme vibration resistance, high colour durability, high efficiency (lumen/Watt) and can benefit from considerably more compact packaging compared to most bulb-type assemblies.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs also offer a potential safety benefit when employed in stop lights; when power is applied, they rise to full intensity approximately 250 milliseconds (¼ second) faster than incandescent bulbs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] This effectively instant rise time theoretically provides following drivers more time to react to the stop light signal, but has not been shown to make cars with LED stop lights less likely to be struck from behind.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs were first applied to automotive lighting in centre high-mount stop lamps (CHMSLs), beginning with the 1986 Chevrolet Corvette (C4).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Adoption of LEDs for other signal functions on passenger cars is gradually increasing with demand for the technology and related styling updates.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The first car registered to drive on the road with full LED rear lights was Land Rover's LCV 2/3 concept car in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] At the time, the only light function that was difficult to reproduce was the reverse light, as white LEDs did not yet exist.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The reverse function was only achievable with the introduction of blue LEDs; by mixing red, green and blue LEDs in a defined distributed pattern behind a lens, white light was produced that conformed to the legal requirements of a reverse light.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The Maserati 3200GT, introduced in 1999, was the first production car to use full LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] In North America, the 2000 Cadillac Deville was the first passenger car with LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2002 Kia Opirus was an early adopter of LED front turn signals.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2007 Audi R8 used two strips of optically focused high-intensity LEDs for its daytime running lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Optional on the R8 outside North America were the world's first LED headlights, made by AL-Automotive Lighting.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The low and high beams, along with the position (parking) light and front turn signal, all use LEDs.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The Lexus LS 600h (XF40) features LED low beam, position and side marker lights in North America, and the 2009 Cadillac Escalade Platinum used LEDs for the low and high beams, as well as for the position and side marker lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222) used entirely LED lights, even in the most basic trim level.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lights are used for flashing beacon lights on vehicles such as maintenance trucks.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Previously, traditional light sources required the engine to continue running to ensure that the battery would not become depleted if the lights were to be used for more than a few hours.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] The energy-efficient nature of LEDs allows them to continue flashing with the engine off.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lighting systems are sensitive to heat.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Due to the negative influences of heat on the stability of photometric performance and the light transmitting components, the importance of thermal design, stability tests, usage of low-UV-type LED modules and UV-resistance tests of internal materials has increased dramatically.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] For this reason, LED signal lights must remain compliant with the intensity requirements for the functions they produce after one minute and after thirty minutes of continuous operation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] In addition, UN Regulation 112 contains a set of tests for LED modules, including colour rendering, UV radiation, and temperature stability tests.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] According to UN Regulations 112 and 123, mechanical, electromechanical or other devices for headlights must withstand endurance tests and function failure tests.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] High-intensity discharge, or HID lights, sometimes referred to as "xenon lights", are modified metal halide lights employing xenon fill gas.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Traditional HID lights, such as those used for general lighting, have a long warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Headlights must provide light very shortly after they are turned on, and the xenon gas serves to reduce warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon light tubes were introduced into series production for the centre high-mount stop light on the 1995 Ford Explorer.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Notable later uses included the 1998 Lincoln Mark VIII with a neon tube spanning the width of the trunk decklid, and the BMW Z8, which made extensive use of neon.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon lights offer the same nearly instant rise time as LEDs, but require a high-voltage ballast.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] In December 2023, Mercedes-Benz received approval in California and Nevada, the only states where it is legal to operate their self-driving vehicles, for turquoise lights in accordance with SAE standard J3134, to indicate to outside observers that the car's self-driving system is engaged.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Mercedes is the first car manufacturer to equip their self-driving vehicles with such lights.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] In distributive light systems, the light from a single source is sent via optical fibres or light guides to wherever it is needed in the automobile.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Light guides are commonly used to distributively light dashboard displays, and premium vehicles are beginning to use distributive systems for lighting such items as door locks, window controls, and cup holders.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/automotive-lighting-p03] Distributive exterior lighting has also been explored, with high-intensity central light sources.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe until English colonisation in the 1600s, Bridgeport was incorporated as a town in 1821 and as a city in 1836.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was a resident of the city and served as the town's mayor in 1871.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum built four houses in Bridgeport and housed his circus in town during winter.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the early 20th century, the city saw an economic and population boom, becoming by all measures Connecticut's chief manufacturing city by 1905.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was the site of the world's first mutual telephone exchange (1877), the first dental hygiene school (1949), and the first bank telephone bill service in the US (1981).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inventor Harvey Hubbell II invented the first American electric plug outlet in Bridgeport in 1912.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Frisbie Pie Company was founded and operated in Bridgeport.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The world's first Subway restaurant opened in the city's North End in 1965.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] After World War II, industrial decline and suburbanization led to the loss of major employers and affluent residents, contributing to poverty and violent crime.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Since the early 21st century, however, the city has undertaken significant redevelopment efforts, and its crime rate fell by nearly 50 percent between 2010 and 2018.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport is home to three museums; the University of Bridgeport, Housatonic Community College, and part of Sacred Heart University; and the state's only zoo.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is officially nicknamed "Park City" due to its 35 public parks, which take up 1,300 acres.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Although none are headquartered within the city itself, more than a dozen Fortune 500 companies are based in its metropolitan area.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has been consistently ranked by various sites as among the 25 most ethnically and culturally diverse American cities.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe during the start of European colonization.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The earliest European communal settlement was in the historical Stratfield district, along US Route 1, known in colonial times as the King's Highway.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Close by, Mount Grove Cemetery was laid out on what was a native village that extended past the 1650s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is also an ancient Paugussett burial ground.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The burgeoning farming community grew and became a center of trade, shipbuilding, and whaling.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was incorporated to subsidize the Housatonic Railroad and rapidly industrialized following the rail line's connection to the New York and New Haven railroad.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was given its name because of the need for bridges over the Pequonnock River that provided a navigable port at the mouth of the river.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Manufacturing was the mainstay of the local economy until the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The first documented European settlement within the present city limits of Bridgeport took place in 1644, centered at Black Rock Harbor and along North Avenue between Park and Briarwood Avenues.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The place was called **Pequonnock** (Quiripi for "Cleared Land"), after a band of the Paugussett, an Algonquian-speaking Native American people who occupied this area.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] One of their sacred sites was Golden Hill, which overlooked the harbor and was the location of natural springs and their planting fields.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (It has since been blasted through for construction of an expressway.) The Golden Hill Indians were granted a reservation here by the Colony of Connecticut in 1639; it lasted until 1802.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (One of the tribes acquired land for a small reservation in the late 19th century that was recognized by the state.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1659, the general court in Hartford established the official borders of the Paugussett Reservation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport's early years were marked by residents' reliance on fishing and farming.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This was similar to the economy of the Paugussett, who had cultivated corn, beans, and squash; and fished and gathered shellfish from both the river and sound.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A village called **Newfield** began to develop around the corner of State and Water Streets in the 1760s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The area officially became known as **Stratfield** in 1695 or 1701, due to its location between the already existing towns of *Strat*ford and Fair*field*.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the American Revolution, Newfield Harbor was a center of privateering.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the time of the State of Connecticut's ratification of the Articles of Confederation in 1781, many of the local farmers held shares in vessels trading at Newfield Harbor or had begun trading in their own name.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Newfield initially expanded around the coasting trade with Boston, New York, and Baltimore and the international trade with the West Indies.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The commercial activity of the village was clustered around the wharves on the west bank of the Pequonnock, while the churches were erected inland on Broad Street.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1787, the Fairfield County Court ordered the laying out and widening of what is now State Street and Main Street in downtown Bridgeport, along the Pequannock River then Newfield.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was assumed before the Revolution that this land would grow into a city.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1800, the village became the Borough of Bridgeport, the first so incorporated in the state.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was named for the Newfield or Lottery Bridge across the Pequonnock, connecting the wharves on its east and west banks.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Bank was established in 1806.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, the township of Bridgeport became independent of Stratford.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, a small community of remaining Golden Hill Pauguasett Natives, along with free blacks and runaway slaves was established in the South End along Main Street known as Little Liberia, with its own churches, schools and hotels, and served as a stop in the underground railroad.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Many remaining Paugusset Indians also lived there.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West India trade died down around 1840, but by that time the Bridgeport Steamship Company (1824) and Bridgeport Whaling Company (1833) had been incorporated and the Housatonic Railroad chartered (1836).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The HRRC ran upstate along the Housatonic Valley, connecting with Massachusetts's Berkshire Railroad at the state line.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was chartered as Connecticut's fifth city in 1836 in order to enable the town council to secure funding (ultimately $150,000) to provide to the HRRC and ensure that it would terminate in Bridgeport.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Naugatuck Railroad—connecting Bridgeport to Waterbury and Winsted along the Naugatuck River—was chartered in 1845 and began operation four years later.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The same year, the New York and New Haven Railroad began operation, connecting Bridgeport to New York and the other towns along the north shore of the Long Island Sound.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Now a major junction, the city began to industrialize.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The city's first immigrants were Irish Catholics who settled in the Sterling Hill section of the Hollow.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Having come to the US to escape the famine, they arrived in town during the 1830s to build the railroad.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They mostly lived in wooden four to six family tenements, often subdivided homes.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum spent a night in Bridgeport, and there met Charles Stratton, a local dwarf.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] He soon became part of Barnum's act and a star under the name "General Tom Thumb".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum moved to Bridgeport and built four houses in the city over the course of his life, the first being Iranistan.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1852, Barnum began an endeavor with William Noble to develop the land (inherited by Noble) on the other side of the Pequonnock River, across the river from Bridgeport to be known as "East Bridgeport" with Washington Park at the center.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The new neighborhood had homes, commerce, and factories, centered around East Main Street.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The neighborhood eventually became the East Side of Bridgeport (occasionally spelled "Eastside").
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1863, during the Civil War, the *Bridgeport Standard* ran a series of articles encouraging the creation of a public park in the city.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum, William Noble and Nathaniel Wheeler to purchase the land on Long Island Sound and donating the land to the city in 1864.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The land on the shore became Seaside Park.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A second park was built near East Main Street, when in 1878, James Beardsley donated more than 100 acres (40 ha) to the city along the Pequonnock River under the condition that the land be "kept the same forever as a public park".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Both parks were designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, known for creating Central Park.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] These two large public parks gave Bridgeport the nickname "The Park City".
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Augustine Cathedral was finished in 1869, built by the Irish who had arrived 30 year earlier.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Saint James Church, predating the Archdiocese of Hartford, was the first Catholic congregation in Fairfield County, starting with 250 members in 1842.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The congregation gave rise to St Augustine's in Sterling Hill, the seat of the Diocese of Bridgeport.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Following the Civil War, the town held several iron foundries and factories manufacturing firearms, metallic cartridges, horse harnesses, locks, and blinds.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Wheeler & Wilson's sewing machines were exported throughout the world.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport absorbed the West End and the village of Black Rock and its busy harbor in 1870.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was elected mayor of the town, which afterwards served as the winter headquarters of Barnum and Bailey's Circus and Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum also helped establish Fairfield County's first hospital (Conn.'s 3rd) and the Bridgeport-Port Jefferson ferry, connecting the town to Long Island.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Harvey Hubbell founded Hubbell Incorporated in Bridgeport in 1888.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Holmes & Edwards Silver Co. was founded in 1882, its wares sold nationally, and the company became part of the International Silver Company in 1898.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (The H&E brand continued well into the 1950s and was advertised in national magazines such as *LIFE* and *Ladies' Home Journal*.) Hungarian immigrants began to arrive, which led to the Ráckόczi Hungarian Aid Association in Bridgeport in 1887 and the American Hungarian Immigrant Aid Society in 1892.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They established themselves in the West End.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1894, Bridgeport's Slavic immigrants played a major role in the development of the Orthodox Christian faith in America when they met with Fr Alexis Toth (now Saint Alexis) and founded Holy Ghost Russian Orthodox Church in the city's Eastside.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This parish became the mother church of all Orthodox Churches in New England.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] From 1870 to 1910, Bridgeport became the largest industrial center in Connecticut; its population rose from around 25,000 to over 100,000, including thousands of Irish, Slovaks, Hungarians, Germans, English, and Italian immigrants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Jewish migration to the city began in the 1881, with an influx of Polish, Russian, and especially Hungarian Jews calling Bridgeport home.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Jew Edwin Land grew up to invent the Polaroid.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1905, Bridgeport was already "the largest industrial center in the state, $49,381,348 was invested in manufacturing and the products being valued at $44,586,519." The city was a port of entry with its imports being valued at around $656,271 in 1908.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Singer factory joined Wheeler & Wilson in producing sewing machines and the Locomobile Company of America was a prominent early automobile manufacturer, producing a prototype of the Stanley Steamer and various luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was also the center of America's corset production, responsible for 19.9% of the national total, and became the headquarters of Remington Arms following its 1912 merger with the Union Metallic Cartridge Co.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Around the time of the First World War, Bridgeport was also producing steam-fitting and heating apparatuses, brass goods, phonographs, typewriters, milling machines, brassieres, and saddles.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Brideport's Italian immigrants settled in the "Central End", today's Little Italy, and the city was the 3rd most Italian in the state by 1910.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Their newspapers were the weekly *La Tribuna de Connecticut* (1906–1908) and later *La Sentinella* (1920–1948) The West End along Wordin Avenue, known as "Hunktown", grew into one of the largest Hungarian communities in the US.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was visited by Hungarian republicans trying to take down the Austro-Hungarian monarchy, in order to garner support.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West Side nearby was home to Slovenians, French-Canadians and Swedish immigrants.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By 1910 Bridgeport had grown into second largest city in Connecticut at 102,052, behind New Haven.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Between 1910 and 1920, during World War I, the city's population exploded from 102,054 to 143,555, due to the city's role in the First World War.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport had the largest factory in the world at the time, the new Remington Arms plant on Boston Avenue (on the East Side).
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Built in 1915, it had 13 separate buildings, each of them 5 stories, connected by a long corridor half a mile long.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The purpose of the building was to fulfil a company order from the Russian tzar for a million rifles and 100 million rounds of ammunition.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The construction site was protected by the National Guard to prevent Bolshevik arson.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory by 1916 employed 16,000 people and led to the construction of "Remington City" in the Mill Hill neighborhood, and "Remington Village" in the East End, by Remington Arms.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the summer of 1915, a series of strikes imposed the eight-hour day on the town's factories; rather than moving business elsewhere, the success spread the eight-hour day throughout the Northeast.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Due to housing shortages in many US cities during World War I, the federal government created the US Housing Corporation.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This resulted in 7 USHC housing developments being built in Bridgeport, notably Seaside Village in the South End and Black Rock Gardens in Black Rock.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By this point, Remington Arms was producing 50% of America's cartridges during the war, with 17,000 employees, and homes for new workers were needed.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory became a General Electric plant after the war.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The First World War had continued the city's expansion so that, on the eve of the Great Depression, there were more than 500 factories in Bridgeport, including Columbia Records' primary pressing plant and a Singer Sewing Machine factory.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The 1920s saw the city's population stabilize at 143,555 after the war.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Roaring Twenties brought more leisure and entertainment.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1919, the city of Bridgeport bought Pleaseure Beach (also known as Steepchase Island) for $220,000.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was an amusement park and beach on an island in the East End next to Stratford.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1920, the city parks commissioner began the process of creating a zoo in Beardsley Park.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport a stop became for performances with around 20 theatres.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 1922 was the year the elegantly designed Majestic and Poli Palace theatres, were built downtown, along with the Savoy Hotel.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Poli Palace theatre (built by Sylvester Poli) was the largest theatre in the state of Connecticut, with gilded hand-carved moldings and vaulted ceilings.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1928, the city bought an 800-acre (320 ha) racetrack and landing field in Lordship to construct Bridgeport Airport.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Spanish immigration in 1920 and 1921 brought hundreds of migrants from Spain, particularly from Pedreguer, Valencia, where "practically the entire town migrated" to Bridgeport.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the Great Depression the city elected Socialist party candidate Jasper McLevy as mayor in 1933.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] McLevy's election made headlines as a New England city had a socialist mayor.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for cutting costs, he would serve as mayor for 12 terms, finally losing in 1957.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Great Migration led southern African-Americans to Bridgeport around the 1930s (thanks to railroads) along with black foreigners (such as Cape Verdean), By 1930, Bridgeport had the third largest percentage of African Americans in New England.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Italian population by 1930 had more than doubled, now the city's largest ethnic group.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The build-up to World War II helped the city's recovery in the late 1930s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Suburban development made its expansion into the undeveloped North End neighborhood.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] On Park Avenue in 1962 the Museum of Art, Science and Industry (MASI) was opened to the public, today's Discovery Museum and Planetarium.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for the newly developed approach of hands on-exhibits, the Museum became science oriented later on.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Continued development of new suburban housing outside of Bridgeport in the city's adjacent suburbs such as Fairfield and Milford attracted middle and upper-class residents, leaving the city with a higher proportion of poor.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the 1960s, Puerto Ricans had begun to immigrate to settle to Bridgeport in large numbers, and by about 1970 had made up 10% of the city's population, or 15,000 people, the largest Puerto Rican population in Connecticut, and they would continue to grow.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Groups such as the local Young Lords branch organized themselves on East Main Street, leading to activism to advance the Puerto Rican community with increased access to health care, better housing, food and an end to poverty and police brutality.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As cities across the country were renovating their central business district after the war, Bridgeport attempted its own urban renewal projects in its old downtown in the early 1960s during the construction of the highways.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hunktown, with a population of 15,000 and the Irish neighborhood in the South End were demolished and replaced with highways and an industrial park.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Trumbull Shopping Park was built just outside Bridgeport city limits in Trumbull in 1965, Connecticut's first fully enclosed shopping mall.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport under Mayor Tedesco went under the 52-acre (21 ha) State Street redevelopment project, demolishing 52 acres of State Street, clearing the land for development.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Replaced with modern high-rise office buildings, parking, the Route 8/25 expressway towards Waterbury and Newtown, and a shopping mall at its core.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Large parts of Main Street were demolished in what was called the Congress Street Renewal project, nothing was built on the land.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Constructed with federal funding, on Lafayette Boulevard and Broad Street, the 450,000 acre, 2 story (with basement) Lafayette Shopping Plaza was erected, a downtown shopping mall with a Sears and a Gimbels department store as anchors connected to it.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Military contracts during the 1950s and 1960s enabled the Bridgeport-Lycoming division of AVCO, founded 1951, to employ at times more than 12,000 people, building tanks, helicopters, and other military hardware.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Decreased demand led to layoffs, and then closure in 1984.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other examples of urban development include two city landmarks, the 12-story 855 Main Street (People's Savings Bank building), and 18-floor Park City Plaza, (State National Bank building) built 1972.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The plan for three identical towers never materialized, due to the Oil Crisis and corporate vacancies.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As such, most skyscraper construction models for downtown Bridgeport from the 70s were never built, unlike Hartford (a city already home to major insurance companies) or Stamford.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Much of north downtown Bridgeport would end up abandoned, neglected and boarded up as department and discount stores closed, leaving only federal and municipal buildings along now empty lots.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Restructuring of heavy industry starting after the mid-20th century caused the loss of thousands of jobs and residents.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like other urban centers in Connecticut, Bridgeport suffered during the deindustrialization of the United States in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was sold 5 years after a rollercoaster caught fire.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The old Bridgeport station caught fire in 1978.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In September 1978, Bridgeport teachers went on a 19-day strike due to deadlocked contract negotiations.
[src:chrysler-lebaron/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A court order, as well as a state law that made strikes by public workers illegal in Connecticut, resulted in 274 teachers being arrested and jailed.
